The Prague Stock Exchange at the End of the Trade
The Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses after the rapid fall in the morning.
Transactions in the Czech Energy Company’s shares amounted to almost half of the usual daily trading.
The Prague Stock Exchange continued its decline from Tuesday’s start, when it fell by almost six percent.
This year, Wall Street shares are falling.
This is also how the market's reaction to the result of the US House of Representatives vote, which refused to support the stabilisation plan of the financial sector there.
Decline in Shares in Asia
Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic fall in stocks on Tuesday, although some of the losses were finally cancelled during the day.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng stock market index described almost four percent during trading, but later it deleted some of the losses and reduced the decrease to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which monitors Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, fell 3.8 percent, and the markets in Shanghai were closed.
The shares of the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but in the end the losses fell to 4.3 percent.
Taiwan's stock market fell 3.6 percent, according to the index there.
“The timing of the U.S. rescue operation is uncertain and affects the world’s financial markets,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Financial Council.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines its monetary policy independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said that U.S. lawmakers should immediately resume negotiations and adopt a proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a threat that other countries will feel the consequences.
The Bloodbath of American Shares
On Monday, the House of Representatives rejected a plan to support the financial system, which should have been spent $700 billion (almost 12 trillion kroner).
The legislators thus ignored President George Bush's call for support for the plan.
Bush said the draft would solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, U.S. stocks were hit by a bloodbath and leading stock indices recorded the biggest decline in 20 years.
The Dow Jones fell almost seven percent, the last time it experienced a similar fall was in 1987.
The index fell before the vote, but as soon as it turned out that the proposal was not adopted in the House, the index started to fall free.
Congress withdraws: U.S. government could pump $700 billion into banks
The Supreme Leaders of the U.S. Congress and the Government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of agreement and financial assistance to the U.S. financial system.
This will be voted on early next week.
U.S. lawmakers have made a breakthrough in negotiations to approve a rescue plan in the form of $700 billion in financial assistance to the U.S. financial system (about 12 trillion kroner).
But there's no victory yet.
Congress needs to complete some of the details of the agreement before they can publish the final form of the law and their vote.
The financial support plan will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
On Sunday, Barney Frank, chairman of the Financial Institutions Committee, informed the Reuters news agency.
According to Senate sources, the draft is likely to be voted on Wednesday as soon as possible.
Economists believe that there should be an announcement that the rescue plan will be approved, which is the first important psychological factor for the revival of financial markets.
However, due to the complexity of the mechanisms, a "sobriety" will then take place.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have taken a big step.
We have resolved our divergent views on what the form of the market stabilisation package should be,” Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat, told Bloomberg.
He said the final vote could take place on Sunday.
Representatives of the legislators met with Henry Paulson, the U.S. Treasury Secretary, on Saturday night to give final form to the government fund.
This should buy up unsellable mortgages from financial companies, which put financial companies in serious losses and jeopardise the stability of the whole system.
“We are close to reaching a final agreement on a plan that will work and that must also be effective on the market.
The repair plan still needs to be continued, but I think we’re there,” Paulson said.
Signal for Asian Trading
The global financial crisis is having a significant impact on stock markets, which are falling sharply.
Senator Harry Reid, a Nevada Democrat, says lawmakers are therefore seeking to reach a final agreement in Congress on Sunday.
This is to reassure investors before the start of trading in Asian financial markets, where the time zone could be the first to influence Monday's trading.
However, it is not yet clear when the two chambers of the U.S. Congress will vote on the law, nor will it be possible for the trial to be blocked at the last minute due to a problem.
Legislators hope that the law will be approved in the coming days.
However, the law still undergoes a number of changes.
The total amount intended to help the system shall be divided into two parts.
According to President Bush’s request, the first $350 billion should be available as soon as possible.
However, Congress can block the issue of the remaining amount, which is set at an additional $100 billion and later $350 billion, if it feels that the program is not fulfilling its function.
Bush assesses progress in negotiations
Although the President may veto this resolution, Congress may override its veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the programme, which was to acquire material assets for the purchase of bad mortgage securities that lost their value, remained, as hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to repay their mortgage loans.
“We worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate should be able to vote on Monday,” Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
U.S. President Bush is pleased with the progress made in the negotiations.
Bush spokesman Tony Fratto said the president was “satisfied with the progress made on Saturday and appreciates the bipartisan efforts to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Limitation of gross severance payments
Christopher Dodd, chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, said that the legislators had agreed on the responsibility for the financial programme, the protection of taxpayers from losses, the closure of discounts and the timing of the financing plan.
The new law also limits the so-called severance payments of the directors participating in the programme and sets up a supervisory committee for the fund.
The fund should be run by the Treasury Department.
“We have worked very hard on this and have made great progress towards an agreement that will work and that will benefit all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also counts on the help of homeowners who are having trouble repaying.
The government should negotiate new installments for the mortgages it buys, with the aim of reducing the monthly installments of debtors and allowing them to keep their houses.
Marek: Spiritual Support
The proposed plan is a good idea, according to David Marek, chief economist at Patria Finance, but it will be very difficult to implement.
This is because it is not possible to know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic actives will be purchased.
This will determine how the financial sector and the government distribute losses among themselves," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
According to Marek, it is not so important that the plan is approved now or at the beginning of next week.
“It is far more important that Congress decide this week to support the plan and give its blessing as soon as possible.
The spiritual significance of reaching an agreement that the plan will be approved is the most important thing at this moment,” Marek said.
Match at the edge: MP3 players vs. mobiles.
We help you choose
While almost all mobile phones can play MP3 files, you can't call with a single MP3 player.
I think it’s better to just buy a phone.
Nevertheless, there are many reasons to get a separate MP3 player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the needs of the prospective owner.
He's probably having a hard time getting a high-quality expensive record player at home to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulenc record.
On the one hand, such musical products do not appear on vinyl records, but there is no objective reason for this in terms of quality.
However, if your shelves are full of art rock, jazz or blues vinyl records, you probably dream of such a record player.
This is similar to travel, i.e. compressed - simplified with MP3 music.
There are also price and quality categories.
For some, it may be unacceptable to issue 8,000 kroner for a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan is likely to find it difficult to accept a 20-kroner market earpiece.
There are two extremes between which there is room for everyone.
There's a lot of choice.
The lifespan of the elements also matters.
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than simply playing music, but also what most mobiles don't do by chance.
No device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, calling and texting, you can play music and video, record both, have a better and worse camera, and even navigate.
And if you take into account smartphones and communicators, you will also have a small computer in your pocket.
This is a small miracle, since no refrigerator can grill and no television can take pictures.
Multi-functional mobile has its drawbacks.
The more functions you use on your mobile, the more the display sends to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few mobile devices can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, mostly much less.
In this regard, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
For cheap phones, you should expect that they will not play for more than a few hours.
Even if you call here and there, get another charger for your workplace just in case - this also applies to more expensive devices.
MP3 players will not have this problem, even worse ones can withstand at least 9 hours of continuous operation with one charge.
The next problem arises when uploading music to mobile.
Unfortunately, only a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, and not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly to the memory card, but only a few card readers can cope without an adapter with miniature memory cards used in mobiles.
With some exceptions (iPod) you do not need any special software.
It is enough to charge the device from the computer with music via USB.
The majority of mobile phones and players already create a music library in order based on the performer himself, the album name, the genre name or, for example, the user's evaluation.
Some devices only represent a tree structure like Windows Explorer, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobiles know more
When choosing a specific device, ask first of all about the battery life, memory capacity, sound output quality and type, and, of course, the comfort of handling.
If the music is primarily a background for you and you only listen to it for a short time a day, for example, on the tram, any mobile playing MP3 is suitable for you.
Any mobile phone can do that.
You don't even have to pay attention to what music formats the mobile or player can play.
All of them can handle MP3, and the vast majority of the music you get will be in this format.
MP3 is one of the most common and the vast majority of devices can cope with WMA music.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPod) is less common.
Better mobile phones also allow you to buy music online, for example.
It is enough to visit the appropriate pages of the service provider (or other service provider) through the mobile Internet and buy the song or album.
This service in itself can be a powerful argument for the purchase of music mobile.
Unfortunately, the offer of service providers is lousy and usually limited to one summer radio hits.
The prices are not the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that such a way of selling music (whether via GSM, Internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people keep their mobile devices with them all the time.
Whenever he feels like listening to something, he gropes his cell phone in his pocket while the forgotten MP3 player lies at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry the headphones or at least the speakerphones with you.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker, which is used by almost all mobile, but only a small number of MP3 players.
For many, the biggest advantage of music phones will probably be the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3,000 kroner.
Between three and four thousand crowns, you can get quite a decent walkman.
Most of the time, however, you are limited by the lack of a conventional earphone output.
The best and most technically equipped phones with traditional 3.5 mm diameter earphones can cost up to 15,000 kroner.
However, the advantage of the players is, among other things, simple operation.
The simplest - by no means necessarily the cheapest players (see our selection) will be dealt with by everyone.
Minimal function, handling similar to a previously standard cassette recorder or gramophone is obvious.
There is no threat of collapse in the form of an accidentally switched-on mobile internet, nor in the form of a huge bill for data transmission.
What equipment to choose
The cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have an opening for removable memory cards (M2, microSD type, etc.).
By buying the right card, you can fit a maximum of two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
The basic types only support cards with a maximum capacity of up to 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones can do with up to 8 GB of memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, choose Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Based on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not need to spend more than 1 100 kroner.
For more demanding listeners, choose special mobile walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsungs).
These devices also have a separate MP3 control button, so the comfort of the treatment is close to the MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, which has the same user interface as MP3 players sold separately, has reached the farthest point in the sector.
MP3 players of the above mentioned brands can provide the same service in the same price range up to four thousand kroner, but with a higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours).
The first virtual service provider will arrive in the Czech Republic later this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively developed and our service providers offer virtually the same services as their Western European partners.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual service provider that forces classic service providers to significantly reduce prices.
Maybe it won't be for long.
On the Mobil.cz website, we have often written that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This has been confirmed by the European Commission, which has pointed out that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in the rest of the EU.
Following the European Commission's latest move, roaming charges may therefore be subject to a controversial situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, text messages from abroad will be cheaper than domestic ones.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This may sound contradictory, as we have three mobile networks and our penetration is well above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are happy to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvorák, President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office, often agrees with this, who has previously stated a few times that there is no place for another service provider in the Czech Republic.
It may be true that the classic service provider with its own network probably does not have much of a chance (although it is probably difficult to find a frequency).
But there is another option - the virtual provider.
It was precisely the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market that brought about a significant price reduction, to which classical service providers had to react.
In the meantime, even before big fish like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market, there were sounds like ours.
However, it has been proven that such service providers have a place and can be truly successful.
However, we do not have to go too far for example.
In February of this year we informed you about the launch of Mobilking virtual service provider in Poland.
In less than six months, this service provider managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest service provider there.
Meanwhile, Mobilking is backed by the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual service providers is the possibility of focusing on a much narrower target group.
In order to operate efficiently, you need a lot less customers than a traditional service provider.
It does not result in relatively high construction, mobile network operation and maintenance costs.
Virtual service providers in the world thus generally appear to be low-cost - they offer cheap calls and sms, which, however, are often offset by fewer services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS messages at least 50% cheaper than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be quite a good move to bet on a target group.
This service is especially focused on men.
“Real men choose the Mobilking service provider – who they like, who they can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual service.
It is difficult to say whether a similar idea can work for us in Poland.
Vodafone’s spokesperson, Miroslav .epick., doubts this: “The Czech market is relatively small for the segmented approach on which the majority of virtual service providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfactory in terms of the supply of services."
In the Czech Republic, there is no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the successful expansion of this project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not seem to be very hopeful.
Mobilking will be launched in other countries in our region," said Jana Studnicová, a spokesman for the financial group Penta, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it showed that existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not very sympathetic to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do their best to avoid any potential competition.
For some time now, the GTS Novera Group has not hidden its interest in the launch of the virtual service provider, which thus intends to take another step towards making Telefonica O2 a real competitor in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in providing not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services to our customers.
The sooner the better.
This possibility has been discussed again with all Czech mobile operators.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl, a spokesman for the group.
Maybe now's a better time.
From unofficial information, it seems that we may be lucky with the first virtual service provider by the end of the year.
However, his birth is still surrounded by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At the moment, we do not believe that a fully-fledged virtual service provider has a place in the Czech market.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very special.
So far, we have not been addressed by a single subject that offers a complex and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sr.e., from the press department of Telefónica 02, mentioned to Mobil.cz.
The other operators also refer to the special situation of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, spokesperson for T-Mobile, in agreement with O2, adds: "So far, we have not recorded any viable and bilaterally beneficial business projects on which it can be based."
And he added: “In the T-Mobile network by the end of the year, it is unlikely that any virtual service provider will show up.
At the moment, we should have a concrete agreement on our table so that we can think in the short term."
Vodafone is more focused on meeting its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav ?epick? adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual service providers, especially in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the most profitable for our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find partners to build networks shared for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible offices - on the same string as service providers
The procedure of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of a new service provider would mean an increase in competition, a decrease in prices and thus a reduction in their profits.
So why should we make it easier to enter such a competition?
When service providers are able to cooperate with something important, they also testify to the huzavona around the birth of U:fon.
The biggest pressure on the T-Mobile company was probably around the birth of its U:phone.
This is evidenced by the publicly available information on the website.
But right now, U:fon is a good argument for why we should not allow the virtual service provider to enter.
Martina Kemrová added: “The environment of the competition in the mobile market has recently been amplified by the access of the fourth mobile operator to the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player into the market and its services would be highly demanding."
However, in view of this attitude of mobile operators, the total lack of interest of Czech regulators is amazing.
In the meantime, it is not just about the attitude of the EU, which, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic, unlike Britain and other developed countries, has no right to interfere in economic competition.
Only the Competition Authority is entitled to do so.
But the office has a specific attitude to the whole problem.
“The entry of the virtual service provider into the mobile market would only be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile service provider and the virtual service provider to lease the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, as the supply of potential interested parties has probably not been sufficiently interesting for traditional service providers," Kristián Chlapua, from the External Relations Department of the Hungarian Competition Authority, mentioned in answer to our question.
A statement by the representatives of the service providers would probably not surprise anyone.
However, the office that should represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, make sure that no one abuses their market position is more than strange.
In particular, if Kristián Chalupa adds: "Foreignly, where virtual service providers generally operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the decline in the price of mobile phone services."
However, the interests of the ÚOHS probably do not include pressure to operate correctly in the market environment and to reduce prices.
In this case, it is truly shocking that the reaction of the three mobile operators is quite touching.
The question of whether it's really just a coincidence is almost self-evident.
Like gas stations, completely identical petrol prices are certainly just the work of chance and hard competition.
"The Office has not detected any signs of anti-competitive proceedings in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
Neither provider has a leading position, i.e. a proportionately greater responsibility for its market activities.
The tools needed to open the mobile market for virtual service providers are probably also missing for the telecom regulator," Chalupa said.
The presentation of the market leadership is one of the many points of dispute.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by TÚ, according to which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, no Czech service provider is in a leading position.
However, some legal experts also offer a different approach - the creation of a virtual service provider always requires the approval of the network operator.
And the mobile operator, relatively logically, has a monopoly on its own network.
So it is necessarily dominant in a certain segment.
But even if we did not accept this argument, it should be at least a warning for ÚOHS that three mobile operators are acting in a strikingly similar way.
Meanwhile, complaints from a range of interested parties (including the already mentioned GTS Novera company) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when negotiating with all service providers.
And putting responsibility on the road is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, with which the ÚOHS takes its hands off the whole case.
We have seen this in similar situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the recently adopted telecommunications law, the extension of the scope of ?Tú's powers in the field of economic competition could not be carried through in telecommunications, although many experts hoped to improve the situation.
Representatives of the NOJS should know this well, but they probably have different interests.
It works when no one is watching.
In the meantime, some kind of pseudo-virtual service providers, many of which are already operating in Czech mobile networks, will remain undetected.
These are companies issuing their own mobile phone service price lists, but they are only partially public.
They are multi-level marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the selected ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic company customer against the service provider, ordering a large amount of SIM cards.
As a special customer, you will receive special offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that the commercial terms of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar pre-emption.
"If there were cases that you were talking about, it could be a breach of terms and conditions that we would deal with and that could lead to the end of cooperation with that company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
But it is highly unlikely that news of this type of activity has not reached the responsible people of mobile operators.
In particular, the three mentioned companies may be thousands of customers.
In the meantime, no service provider will defend itself against such a procedure.
They have a significant profit from the activities of these companies, and, unlike real virtual service providers, they do not particularly threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav ?epick? warns of possible problems: "The law allows similar speculations, however, only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not in their name, so they cannot have it in full as a general customer of mobile operators."
But that's exactly what the U.S. should be strange about.
There is also another question for the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to a similar procedure, why are they hindering the birth of a virtual service provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has a relatively strong power to expose such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the service providers that they did not suspect anything of this kind and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we are not the most expensive
As has already been mentioned a few times in the text, the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market has resulted in a noticeable price reduction of services.
In the meantime, in virtually all countries where virtual service providers have been established, classic service providers have tried to prevent their creation more or less.
The arguments they used were practically the same - too small, perhaps too satisfied a market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was precisely at this moment that regulators intervened, which in no way protected the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Then, either through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual service provider, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory authorities are giving each other the whole case.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that unclear competences are good for them in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider is really coming soon, the Czech mobile market may start to move again.
If a service provider would allow the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, it is difficult for the ÚOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of further interested parties.
And compared to the rest of Europe, we may not be making more expensive calls anymore.
