Prague Transport Company Delivers Chip Card for the First Time on Wednesday
Wednesday 1 October 2008 enters itself into the history of Prague Transport Company as the first passenger to get into metros, trams and buses who will have an electronic coupon in his pocket instead of a paper ticket.
The coupon is currently available to about 100,000 people who have the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase 30-day, 90-day, and annual coupons (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time save them on their chip cards in the information centres and offices of the Transport Company at Muzeum, M?stek, Nádra?í Hole?ovice, And?l, Roztyly, Let?any, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Ka?erov and Luka metro stations.
From yesterday, coupons can be purchased online through the Transport Company's www.dpp.cz website.
The service was used by more than 400 customers until the afternoon.
Those who start using online trading can finally forget about the windows of metro stations, where they have had to regularly stand through long lines for tickets.
The coupon can be purchased online and saved on the Opencard card in one of the 13 branches of the City Library.
"In these places, passengers have a counter with trained servers to help interested parties shop online and save their purchased coupons on their cards," said Martin Opatrna, a spokesman for the project.
In addition to libraries, electronic coupons can be saved to Opencard in self-service vending machines equipped in some lobbys.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket handlers, and passengers may have already noticed them at Roztyly, Bud.jovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
“There are currently five of them in the city, but there should be 80 by the end of the year,” added Opatrna.
Automatic check of the coupon instead of the driver
Managing the vending machines that start their operation tomorrow is simple.
Just insert the Opencard chip card and save the previously paid coupon on your own.
From tomorrow, electronic coupons will be valid not only in the capital, but also in its surroundings.
So on trains and bus lines around the city from 300 to 499, with which the inhabitants of the Central Bohemia districts travel primarily to the capital city.
"On trains classified as integrated transport in Prague, conductors were equipped with card readers to determine the zone validity of coupons," explained Filip Drápal from the Ropid organization that compiled Prague public transport schedules.
In buses around the city, card readers are installed at the driver's checkout.
Thus, when boarding, the driver must not only show the chip card, but also place the Opencard in the place specified on the side of the cashier.
This is how the driver checks the validity of the coupons.
“If, for example, the passenger needs to check the validity of the coupons, the easiest way is to ask the driver to do so,” Dráp added.
Passengers who do not travel by bus around the city and do not remember when their coupon expires can go to self-service vending machines that save coupons on cards again.
Information on the validity of their documents is displayed here on the equipment display.
The Sudeten wanted a referendum from the United States.
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans asked to be attached to the United States of America.
This is revealed by the letter in the collection of the South Bohemian Science Library.
If we can't be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
It is said that this was the wish that some groups of Sudeten Germans turned to the President of the United States in 1945.
This is also revealed by a letter preserved from a private archive, which is now kept in the collection of the South Bohemian Science Library.
In the letter, the Germans of Cesky Krumlov ask the U.S. President not to allow the return to the Czech Republic of the "County of .umava", which was occupied by Hitler under the Munich Treaty.
"We have interpreted the situation correctly and we really want to be sure of the words that the American troops are not coming to the German territories as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," it says in the letter, signed with the words "People who care about the fate of .umava."
Since the attachment to Czechoslovakia is supposed to give the Sudeten Germans, in addition to knowing the Czech national character, only hope for brutality, ruthlessness, not understanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the US President to take over the protectorate over .umava "now and forever".
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the opinion of four million people, it would condemn this area to us as a foreign country, which would oppress and destroy the minority and contribute almost nothing to the victory of the Allies," the letter said.
