Rats have emotions, too.
A rat or a moth is on the run in case of danger. Does that mean you feel fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that animals have emotions.
But how can we test whether they feel the same way when they act like us?
Famous scientists have been publishing their articles in the Internet magazine "Edge" for years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE is looking at the answers to the question "What do you think is real without proving it?" in one of its series.
I believe that animals have emotions and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it. It is true that we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
In this case, however, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as we look at other species and examine the issues of perception or consciousness in general, we arrive in difficult terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: pretends to be dead, escapes or attacks.
People behave in a similar way, from which some researchers conclude comparable subjective experiences.
But I don't believe that.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our own subjective experiences to animals.
On the one hand, circuits related to human consciousness almost always contain the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and execution/management functions).
This wide area is more advanced in man than in other primates, and it seems to be completely absent in other organisms.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, such as the knowledge of who we are, or the ability to design and decide, it is reasonable to assume that man is different from other primates.
Another dramatic feature lies in the linguistic nature of man: Since a significant part of the human experience is related to language, it is often claimed that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals can be excluded.
However, even if consciousness did not depend on language, language would certainly influence it, so animal consciousness, whatever its nature, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may be like for other animals.
If consciousness cannot be measured as an internal and subjective thing, and because of the special hardware it cannot be analysed on the basis of our own experience, then his research presents us with serious problems.
Most of my discussion relates to the content of conscious living, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that is probably more accessible to science.
The processes of consciousness of animals, regardless of their content, could be examined, and this is exactly what happens in experiments on the short-term memory of primates, especially in the example of visualization.
However, in this assumption examined by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, they rely more on the neural connections of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: both can be the same or not.
Interestingly, this assumption also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex in the creation of visualization.
What does this mean for emotions?
This is due to the fact that an emotional system, such as fear, is activated in the brain aware of its own activity.
What we call "fear" is therefore the mental state in which we are when the activity of the defensive system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies a working memory.
Thus, emotions are closely related to those areas of the cerebral cortex that are characteristic of primates and, in particular, humans.
In addition to the linguistic form, perception is divided into fine degrees, because with the help of words and grammar we are able to distinguish and categorize states in order to describe them to others in addition to ourselves.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio, for example, is of the opinion that emotions come from simpler activities in the areas of body perception of the cerebral cortex and the brain stem, as well as Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it can easily play a role in the emotions of species.
In theory, I can't deny that, but I think it's unprovable.
Pankseep believes that what appears to be fear in rats and humans is probably also felt in both cases: How can you check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave in the same way?
A cockroach escapes in case of danger, does he also feel fear?
In my opinion, only similar behavior is not proof of the same experience.
Although neural comparisons help: rats and humans have similar brains, cockroaches do not have brains.
But is the brain stem responsible for emotions?
And even if this could be proven in humans, how could we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, and maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have emotions.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And since their emotions are suspected to be fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to investigate the emotional behavior of rats rather than emotional emotions.
In any case, progress in this area is promising at the neural level, if we measure the same in rats and humans.
Like rats, I don't research language and consciousness, I don't research emotions, because I don't know if they exist.
To others, this may seem like a short-sighted attitude, but I'd rather move forward than keep hitting a wall.
I am a practical emotionalist.
