On Monday, the concern again captivated investors even after congressional leaders announced that they had reached an agreement over the weekend on the economic rescue operation, which is the largest in history.
The news was clouded by concerns that the financial crisis would not end for a long time.
As the latest event of the unfolding crisis, Citigroup will acquire the banking business of Wachovia Corporation, the government announced on Monday.
In the meantime, the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg have partially nationalised the European financial conglomerate Fortis.
According to Barclays Capital analysts, as a result of desperate weekend negotiations, "it seems that the rescue operation has failed to revive the stock market trading mood."
As the economic situation deteriorates, it is expected that demand for commodities, such as oil, will also fall.
“The future of the stock market, interest rates and currency exchange rates around the world has become uncertain,” a Deutsche Bank analyst wrote.
“We believe that the commodity market will not escape the ‘epidemic.’
The biggest question for the commodity market is to what extent the U.S. "sickness" infects the whole world, especially China."
As oil consumption declined as a result of the slowdown in economic growth, bank analysts cut their expectations for next year, reducing their forecasts for oil and gas prices by 20% for 2009.
In the second quarter, the team set a record.
After spending more time in the Jets jersey than anyone else in the last eight seasons, Shaun Ellis, playing in the defensive end position, thought he had seen everything.
But then he watched the second quarter unfold on Sunday, when the Jets turned a pointless game into a sensational match.
"I've never seen anything like it," Ellis said.
The second quarter began after the lukewarm game of Jets and Arizona Cardinals was in full harmony with the dark clouds towering in the sky.
Brett Favre, quarterback, gave a 12-yard touchdown pass to Laveranues Coles. This became the perfect forerunner of an afternoon in which their cooperation developed significantly.
Favre gave Coles two more touchdown passes in this quarter, including when two cornerbacks fell in a row 10 seconds before the end of the half.
"I didn't regret the trouble," Favre said of all the passes he gave Coles.
"Hell is a good player.
We've been able to communicate well with each other, no matter what people think."
While Favre and Coles were playing ball, the defense stopped Cardinals quarterback Kurt Warner.
The cornerback Darrelle Revis caught a bad pitch and threw it back 32 yards, which was a touchdown.
Eric Smith, a safety player, reached into another pass and got the ball.
David Bowens, linebacker managed to knock the ball out of Warner's hand.
