The rested Gebrselassie breaks his own world record
Once again, the Ethiopian Haile Gebrselassie showed why she was considered by many to be the best mid- and long-distance runner ever, when she broke her own world record in Berlin on Sunday, making her the first to run the 42.2 km in 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With the victory on a comfortable flat track in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie improved 27 seconds on his previous result of 2:04:26, which he achieved in Berlin last year.
By the age of 35, Gebrselassie set the 26th world record of her career in so many areas that she won the World Championship or reached a world record in almost every run from 1500 metres to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie missed the Beijing Olympic marathon, which, in retrospect, may have proved to be too cautious, fearing that air pollution would exacerbate his asthmatic problems.
Instead, he entered the Berlin marathon.
In almost perfect conditions - sunny weather, initially at 9 degrees and at the end at 13 degrees - Gebrselassie won on Sunday at an incredible speed of 2 minutes 56 seconds per kilometre.
Since non-marathon runners such as Gebrselassie and Kenyan Paul Tergat turned to longer distances, the marathon record has fallen by more than two minutes in the last decade since the Brazilian Ronaldo da Costa won 2:06:05 in Berlin in 1998.
After Sunday's victory, Gebrselassie told reporters that two weeks ago, his two calves cramped and he couldn't train for two weeks.
Obviously, during the forced rest, he was refreshed and not rusted.
"I'm so happy," Gebrselassie told reporters.
"Everything worked out perfectly.
I started training again a week ago, and today I had doubts, but in the end everything was fine."
He received some criticism, especially from Kenya, Ethiopia's East African rival, that he uses too many aids in his competitions, usually avoids many world-famous marathon runners, relies on his pacers as if he were running on track and puts world records ahead of competitive spirit.
However, this criticism hardly reduces Gebrselassie's greatness in long-distance running.
Gebrselassie reached the midpoint at 1:02:04 on Sunday with the help of four Kenyan pace runners.
Two top Kenyan runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, gave Gebrselassie the rhythm after the pace runners were tired.
Not much more than 4.8 kilometers ahead of the finish line, Gebrselassie left Kwambai with a last sprint, who finished second with 2:05:36, improving his individual best by 5 minutes.
Kamathi came in third at 2:07:48.
In the women's competition, Kazakhstan-born Irina Mikitenko, now a German citizen, ended a remarkable year with her seventh fastest victory of 2:19:19.
The world record is held by British Paula Radcliffe with a time of 2:15:25.
Last spring, 36-year-old Mikitenko won the London marathon with a 2:24:14 result.
He was unable to participate in the Beijing Olympics because of his alleged back injury, but he quickly recovered and won the Berlin marathon, where he improved his individual peak by five minutes.
He won the race with a clever calculation: for the first time he allowed a group of four Ethiopians and Kenyans to advance and gain significant leadership, and after running about 30 km, he went after them.
Ethiopian Askale Tafa Magarsa finished second with a time of 2:21.31, while Kenyan Helena Kiprop came third with a result of 2:25:01.
A separate city, the pride and ordeal of the blacks
In the adventure park in Greater Orlando - a few miles from everything that gleams, loud and powerful - there hides a quiet small town where the pride and complications of the African-American experience were born.
Eatonville, the first purely black city to integrate into the country, and which was Zora Neale Hurston's childhood home, is no longer as simple as it described in 1935: "the five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, a lot of guavas and two schools without prison."
It's a pilgrimage place now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have already attended the annual Zora Festival. The Eatonville celebration series is held in honor of the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance, Hurston.
Yet, in many ways, the city he described and made a tourist attraction, which is also included in the Florida guidebook published by the Federal Writers' Project of the Crisis Age, is separate from its surroundings.
As independent, dignified and closed-minded as it was in the 1930s, Hurston wrote that urban blacks in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with white people who "know so little about us that they don't know what they're missing."
Even in the year when the black presidential candidate, Barack Obama, encourages an open exchange of views on the racial issue, many here are distrustful of the glances of outsiders.
“We are very careful about how our story is told,” said Hortense Jones, 59, who has lived here his entire life and is a member of the city’s oldest church.
"You have to say it right."
Eatonville has long been characterized by the paradox of victory and struggle.
At the same time, it is a historical model of black stand, but at the same time a community of nearly 2,400 people, where poverty rates reach twice the national average.
Partly a literary node, and partly an example of the sometimes despised, sometimes praised, southern, urban, black culture that flourishes in the shadow of oak trees.
It is not surprising, therefore, that the inhabitants here are proud and defensive at the same time.
And the image of Eatonville has been important since Zora (everyone here calls Hurston that).
In books written in honest, strong dialects, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937), he introduced his hometown to the world.
The five paragraphs of the Florida guidebook transformed the city, which lies along Route 17. This road leads from the long-forgotten center of Florida to one of the venues of black history and human drama.
Hurston, who was brave in both life and literature, introduced his readers to Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then looked into the more intimate spheres.
He wrote: "To the right of the road we find the modern public school, on a brown basis with a white border, carefully maintained courtyards and playgrounds, which Howard Miller takes care of, although he can hardly read and write."
He mentioned the widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of drinks and anything that might be needed at the temporary shelters."
So in a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to autonomy, but also to illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
Clearly, the Fodor's guidebook presented it differently.
This description was not liked by everyone.
“Zora told things as they were,” reported 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson’s girls. Hurston immortalized them by quoting the slippery songs men sang about their beauty.
He added: "Some people didn't like it."
Hurston is still remembered here as the living eccentric who often visited home after his family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston stormed into town, he usually arrived unannounced in a roaring Chevrolet, smoking cigarettes, and wearing long pants in a city where people are still proud of their dignified clothing.
Most people were fascinated, Franklin said, but many were forked.
“People were always happy to see Zora,” Franklin said.
However, on the terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, he added, swinging in his chair: "He never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor, and his books were no longer published.
It seemed that Eatonville, along with most of the world, had forgotten about it.
Although she was once a popular writer, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived before.
In Eatonville, there were no major commemorations or large public readings.
“I don’t think they understood how much he enriched the world or what he left us at all,” said Valerie Boyd, author of the 2003 Hurston biography, “Wrapped in a Rainbow.”
The turning point came in 1980.
Orange County officials wanted to build a five-track road through the city instead of the two-track main street, Kennedy Avenue, which played an important role in the life of the community.
The expanding Orlando has already penetrated the Interstate 4 motorway connecting the states on the western border of the city.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering after a difficult historical period.
Among other things, forced integration put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the struggles of racial mixing gave the community a taste of hatred.
“At that time, a group of white boys came over and threw oranges and other things at people on the side of the road,” Franklin said.
"There was a woman who died from this.
They threw a watermelon out of a car."
In a letter to The Orlando Sentinel in 1955, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's decision to force integration, saying of the "Brown v. Board of Education" decision: "It offends rather than respects my race."
Today, residents say that although desegregation of schools was positive in some respects, it weakened the unity of the Eatonvilles and undermined young people’s self-confidence.
“Black children are used to being hugged – I remember – by a teacher in the morning and in the evening,” said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins, executive director of the non-profit organization “Preserve the Community of Eatonville.”
“This lasted as long as the students and teachers came from a common place,” he added.
“We didn’t hug our white teacher because he was a white teacher – I mean there were cultural differences between us,” Nathiri said.
However, human rights have helped many other Zora Neale Hurston rise - in black writers, actors and artists who have overcome prejudices, as she has, with such optimistic self-confidence and lines as: "How can anyone deprive himself of the pleasure of my company!
It is incomprehensible to me.”
In 1975, Alice Walker made a pilgrimage to Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight to restore her reputation.
Five years later, a respected Hurston biography written by Robert E. Hemenway was placed on the shelves of bookstores, which once again placed him among America’s role models.
The road construction project would have started just as Eatonville’s most famous daughter was once again at the center of attention.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw him as a savior.
The community started organizing a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the county would destroy with its main road.
Thousands of fans have come to the opening event two years later, and many have returned to the ceremony every January.
Several years later, the county abandoned its road construction proposal.
“The five-tracking of the main road has revived the community and brought it to full speed, which is a real civic pride,” Nathiri said.
Boyd put it more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the road construction project helped to change the city's image of itself.
An increasing number of people outside the city appeared, such as lawyer Rachelle Munson, who began attending church here in 1993, and the locals began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the national historical list in 1998.
In 2006, the new one-story library (of course named after Hurston) was opened on Kennedy Avenue, re-covered and beautiful.
Eatonville remains Florida's cuckoo egg: it's less than ten kilometers from the center of Orlando, but sometimes it feels like a suburban side street during summer rain; it's as small as when it was founded by 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Today, 90% of the inhabitants are black.)
They still welcome the outsiders who come here looking for Eatonville's story.
Most interviews require prior permission, and some things, such as Eatonville's oldest fresco, painted by a white man and depicting blacks working in the fields, should not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, including the confident teacher Jones, who is particularly attracted to bright red, fear that their separate community will be misunderstood.
And yet, as the Hurston Festival grew wider, the pride of the hometown grew.
In particular, young people increasingly view Eatonville as Hurston saw his own race: wonderful, with his problems and everything, neither better nor worse, just as proud, creative, diligent, foolish and confused as other racial and ethnic groups in America.
There is an honest civil bond in the words of Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return after graduating from college to work for the local government or the police, which he believes need help.
And it seems that younger people have also learned to describe Eatonville correctly, such as 11-year-old Winter Park twins Alondra and Alexia Kenon.
“Most people who just travel through here think this city is nothing compared to the others,” Alondra Kenon said on Sunday.
“But if you stop and take a little time to get to know your history, this is a very beautiful city.”
We all speak the language of finance here in New York.
Nothing has changed on the surface.
If tourists didn't care about the newsstand booths and the huge television projectors in Times Square, they wouldn't realize they were in the middle of a storm.
They would never realize that with the glass-walled, beehive-shaped offices over their heads, the bankers and venture fund managers who control New York have been living the most difficult days since 1929.
Couriers still rattle their metal tea carts down the sidewalks, carrying trays filled with muffins for morning meetings.
There are still Spanish - speaking men shuffled among the blockhouses, carrying like a human mule 50 or so ironed shirts hanging on a yoke-like noose across their shoulders.
Office workers are still waiting in line for their morning sweet pastries at the food trucks on the sidewalk, and it is still impossible to catch a taxi between 4:00 and 7:00 p.m. on weekdays.
I didn’t feel any crisis until Thursday afternoon, despite all the ominous news, I decided to open a new bank account.
Even though I was deliberately planning to settle the matter in the local branch of my JP Morgan Chase bank during the afternoon’s calm, there were about 20 people in line before me.
Not at the bank teller's window, where money can be taken or paid, but at the customer service desk, where older customers order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to Macy's store, and where new customers open bank accounts.
Many before me - I learned later from Starr, the banker "assigned to me" - lined up with the same intention as I did.
However, unlike me, they have already taken their money out of smaller banks in their homes, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Staten Island.
They took money from so-called savings banks (which are like housing cooperatives), credit unions, and small-town savings banks that operate in only one state and allegedly treat their customers as family members.
In the last year, 15 of these banks have been quietly destroyed.
In recent days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in capital, has been in receivership, and when New Yorkers left on Friday night for the weekend, another bank, Wachovia, made a savings of $440 billion.
The office and shop workers before me, fearing another collapse, moved their money to a bank that seemed to be a safe haven, a bank that makes the most capital injection buyouts on Wall Street.
Over the past few weeks, ordinary people in New York have become experts in finance.
A woman at a local Chinese store on her phone talked about the bankrupt Lehman Brothers bank and its huge-looking CEO Dick Fuld as if she were complaining about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed janitor on my apartment block in his fifties, has changed the subject, and we're not talking about Brad and Angelina or my food shipment, as usual.
He said to me after I went to the bank: "I invested all my savings in money market instruments.
I've changed, I'm not taking any chances."
Muslim graves desecrated while Austria tilted to the right
Heinz-Christian Strache, from the right-wing Austrian Freedom Party, and Filip Dewinter, from the Belgian right-wing party Vlaams Belang, took part in a demonstration in Antwerp on Thursday, January 17, 2008, at which the organization "Citys Against the Rise of Islam" was introduced.
They marched with signs imitating traffic signs depicting mosques crossed with a red line.
According to police, far-right extremists are responsible for the desecration of Muslim cemeteries in Austria, which took place on the same weekend when far-right parties made significant progress in national parliamentary elections.
More than 90 graves were severely damaged at the Traun cemetery near Linz, sometime between Friday night and this morning.
The perpetrators drew Jewish symbols with spray paint, such as the Star of David, on some graves, but investigators say they were just trying to hide their extreme motives, which stem from hatred against Muslim immigrants.
It is not clear whether the incident is related to the elections in any way.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were "deeply shaken" by the grave desecration that took place shortly before the end of the Muslim religious month, Ramadan.
Meanwhile, Austria is conducting a conscience check following yesterday's parliamentary elections, during which the political balance has tilted to the right.
The two far-right parties, which won almost 30% of the votes, campaigned for the Future of Austria, a strong anti-immigration law, and some of their slogans were labeled xenophobic by their critics.
Heinz-Christian Strache, President of the Freedom Party, who won more than 18% of the votes, also expressed his disapproval of the food allegedly associated with Islam.
At the final general assembly of the party in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" that would prevent the strengthening of Islam.
Both parties want to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, arguing that they are political symbols of the ongoing Islamization of Austria and Europe.
According to polls and analyses carried out immediately after the elections that brought victory to the far right, the change was due to the largely young voting base, who are concerned about their future in the European Union.
Garry Glitter banned from traveling abroad
Garry Glitter, a well-known rock star convicted of raping children, was banned from travelling to France and Spain.
The judges decided to ban Glitter for six months after notifying the authorities that he intended to travel to Spain through France.
Kent police obtained a travel ban on Thursday after submitting evidence to the court of convictions for child rape against Glitter.
Glitter, whose real name is Paul Gadd, did not attend the Ashford Magistrates trial in Kent, but was represented by Corker Binning's lawyers.
A court spokesman said: "On Thursday, 25 September, Kent police filed a request with the Ashford Magistrates Court to prevent Paul Gadd's planned trip to France and Spain on 25 March.
"Paul Gadd didn't show up in person."
The 64-year-old Glitter informed the authorities of his intention to travel abroad because he was obliged to do so by the law on the register of sex offenders.
You must notify the authorities if you intend to travel abroad for more than three days.
You must also notify the police at least seven days before your planned departure.
If you do not notify the authorities, you may be sentenced to up to five years in prison.
Kent police said they don't want to talk about individual cases within Glitter County and possible whereabouts.
A spokesman for the Kent Police said: "The Kent Police are doing everything they can to protect children both within the country and abroad.
“In our opinion, it’s easier to control someone if they don’t leave the UK because we have a comprehensive system here to manage potential risks more effectively.
"The most important task of the Kent Police is to protect the population of Kent. Through close cooperation, we constantly monitor the behaviour of those who are registered as sex offenders and who live in the county to minimise the potential risks to the population."
Glitter returned to the UK last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for raping a 10- and 11-year-old girl.
After his release, he flew to Bangkok, where he was supposed to board a plane to London.
However, he claimed that he felt bad and refused to fly to London.
The authorities in the country wouldn't let him pass the passport check, so he finally flew to Hong Kong.
The Chinese authorities also refused to allow him to enter the country, so he flew back to Bangkok, where local police and immigration officials insisted on returning to Britain.
Finally, he arrived at Heathrow Airport Terminal 3 on 22 August and stayed there until his lawyer, David Corker, went to court in West London, Uxbridge, because, according to Scotland Yard's application, he was entered in the register of sex offenders under a court order.
Glitter had previously spent four months in prison in the UK in 1999 for possession of photographs of child rape.
According to a source at the Ministry of Interior, Jacqui Smith, State Secretary for Home Affairs, welcomed the fact that Glitter was not allowed to travel to France and Spain.
“I don’t take photos on stage because I want to present the artist from a personal point of view.” – Günther Bauer
No sets, no ruffles, no dance shoes.
The great masters of flamenco at close range, without the excitement of the performance: to get to know the everyday faces of the dancers.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, ordinary people.
And these two sides cannot be separated, except in intimate moments far from the audience, when we can look at a personal movement, grasp the depth of a caught look, or marvel at the beauty of the passive but expressive hand of the artist who is not preparing for his performance on the stage.
In his photo series Günther Bauer Flamenco-people, Germany, he combines the theatricality of singers, dancers and guitarists with this less known everyday side of the masters.
Through the photos, flamenco presents its unique iconography from different angles.
The exhibition, which is part of Flamenco Photography Month, "reflects the growing international importance of flamenco," the creator believes, adding that Flamenco-people "could be anyone, as the images make the observer realize that these images do not typically depict artists.
These people caught on the street are artists who can bring passion, sadness, joy to the stage... and capture the audience.
At the same time, stage photography is not suitable for capturing their personality.
Their personality and character reside in the depths of their being.
I wanted to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of the greats of flamenco with the help of the camera."
With the momentum of the Cante de las Minas festival, Bauer started his long journey in 1997, during which he made portraits of flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers with a record camera.
These portraits evoke classical photography thanks to the camera and the choice of subject.
However, the use of various stylistic tools breaks with traditional visual representation and suggests modernity. The following idea faithfully reflects Bauer's idea of flamenco: "This is a music with traditional roots, which, however, changes day by day and is always fascinating."
It's not the dance, it's not the song or the music in itself, it's the artist's personality and character that charms the audience.
In recent days, the main motif of the works you can see in the El Fotomata gallery is the search for an encounter with its essence, the artistic enchantment, which becomes visible through the way of perception, existence and presentation.
The well-known figures of flamenco, including Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, are the hallmarks of this photo collection of almost 60 artists.
The project also became a flamenco anthology, which will soon be published in an album covering portraits presented at the exhibition.
Bauer's passion for portraits two years ago encouraged him to repeat the idea with the series "Portraits of Veteran Athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concept of Flamenco-people is slightly different, the photographer adds: "I really like to photograph people, get to know them and enter their lives for a longer or shorter moment.
In my opinion, the most difficult genre of photography is portrait.
People you meet, people you meet, people you sometimes don't even know, or people who only take a few minutes to take a picture.
But despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realize my ideas.
The exhibition entitled Flamenco-people, selected from the portraits of contemporary flamenco, can be seen in the El Fotomata Gallery, parallel to Alameda de Hércules, until 16 October.
