Repeated drunk drivers will be obliged to install "Alcolock"
The Ministry of Interior would require the driver to install a device that would prevent the vehicle from starting if the driver is drunk or does not blow into the device.
The proposal was tabled in June and is currently being dealt with by the State Attorney's Office, according to which the pilot project will take one year.
Since the aim of the project is to restore the car to the market, the driver will also have to take part in a repeat course on transport education.
In addition to the General Prosecutor's Office for Transport Safety, the Directorate-General for Transport (DGT) and the Institute of Automotive Safety Technology Foundation (FITSA) are also involved in the experiment.
According to statistics, 30-75% of drivers arrested several times for drunk driving get back in the car.
This would be prevented by Alcolock, as the system connected to the vehicle determines the alcohol level of the sprayed air. If it is higher than allowed, or if the driver has not blown into the device at all, the system will not allow the car to start.
The cost of the instrument of more than EUR 1000 would be borne by the violator.
A 2007 study in the USA showed that vehicles equipped with these instruments could reduce the number of violations by up to 65% in the first year after installation.
In Spain, it is estimated that this rule could save 115 lives a year.
The measure focuses on offences for two reasons: on the one hand, it makes it easier to prevent them from turning into criminal offences,
On the other hand, it is easier to introduce it, as the implementation of the legal reform is in the usual way, while the necessary criminal reform would require an amendment to the basic law.
The instrument is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although it has already been installed in some industrial and public service vehicles in experimental mode.
The House of Representatives will vote tomorrow on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party to install the system in school buses, on a French model.
