People who talk in their dreams
Some kids talk at night.
I don't mean those who wake up and tell me fully awake what happened to them that day, but those who talk while they sleep.
The phenomenon may seem scary at first, but it's actually completely harmless.
This benign sleep disorder is called somniloquismus.
It is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
I'm sure many of you have been told that he spoke at night.
In terms of frequency, it can be completely rhapsodic (for example, it occurs only once in a disease with high fever) or more regular (daily, once a week or once a month), and usually the next day the child does not remember anything.
Its appearance cannot be traced back to a single cause.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, night alarms, enuresis nocturna or sleepwalking, but this is not legal.
As mentioned above, it can be a condition with a high fever, or even an accompanying phenomenon of stress or increased excitement.
In any case, it's been little studied so far.
The intensity of speech is also very variable.
It may be quiet, calm, may consist of incoherent words, murmuring, but contrary to all this, it may also appear in the form of shouting, crying, or longer speech.
If the phenomenon is very intense, it is recommended to observe the child and turn to a specialist. The examination can reveal whether there is a problem that causes great anxiety and can therefore offer a solution.
As mentioned above, it is a benign phenomenon, and consequently there is no cure unless it is associated with another treatable form of sleep disorder (e.g. insomnia or stress).
However, there are a few things you can do, here are some preventative measures:
Make sure that the child remains calm before going to bed.
Choose comforting toys and avoid watching scary or more aggressive TV shows or shows.
Children who tend to be nervous or have difficulty relaxing are taught some relaxation methods to help them find inner calm.
This will help the child to sleep more comfortably.
If he does start talking while we're sleeping, let's try to stay calm.
Remember, it's harmless to the child, and the next day, they won't remember anything.
Useful advice
Don't wake the child.
It would be unnecessary because the child is unconscious, but he would get out of sleep.
Even though he's talking, he's actually sleeping and resting longer.
Remember, if you have multiple episodes of severe anxiety, it is advisable to consult a specialist or explore what triggers a high level of anxiety in your child.
If you speak clearly (this is the rarer case), do not start asking questions to learn anything from him.
It would be unnecessary anyway, since he is not conscious enough to collect his thoughts during sleep.
On the other hand, you only hear the speech, but you do not see the dreams associated with it, so be careful with the interpretation of what you hear and the possible conclusions.
Never tell a child that you can ask him about his secrets at night.
Not even for fun.
This causes a great deal of anxiety.
So the most important thing is not to worry, because it's just a few minutes of harmless episode.
