The presidential visit coincides with a meeting of the "crisis committee", set up by Breton fishermen to initiate action against the rise in gas oil prices, as oil prices exceeded the record average price of EUR 1.14 per litre.
David Martinon, a spokesman for the President of the Republic, said the president would "negotiate with fishermen on ways to help companies regain their competitiveness and make working conditions and wages safer for sailors."
The fishermen are eagerly awaiting the arrival of Nicolas Sarkozy.
On Tuesday morning, demonstrations were held in Morbihan and Calvados counties, causing nearly 10 km of congestion.
They also paralysed the transport of Quiberon's yacht port, but the roads to Belle-Ile were not blocked.
Roadblocks have been placed on the Quiberon Peninsula.
On Monday, the sailors had already shown their determination, and at dawn, tyres and pallets were set on fire outside the fuel warehouses at the ports of Brest, while protests took place in Concerteau and Saint-Brieuc.
For example, in Sables d'Olonne, Vendée County, fishermen did not board a ship, while in Le Havre some 20 ships hindered the traffic of commercial ships.
In the evening, the fishermen of La Turballe and Le Croisic in the county of Loire-Atlantique removed the huge Total oil refinery blockade in Donges.
The fishermen of Boulogne-sur-Mer, however, have decided to wait for Wednesday’s meeting in the Ministry by deciding on further steps.
In Le Guilvinec, the "crisis committee" will have to decide on its next step and participation at the planned meeting at the Paris Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries on Tuesday.
However, some Breton fishermen do not want their interests to be represented by the heads of the National Fisheries Committee, as the Committee did not support their efforts.
"The strike continues because fishermen refuse to go to Paris," said Liliane Cariou, chairman of the Lorient Fisheries Commission.
Professional fishermen who do not pay taxes on diesel are currently paying around 50 cents per litre, but they believe that a ship would only be profitable if the price of diesel fell below EUR 0,30 per litre.
