The silence of the night falls again on October Square.
On television, President Lukashenko and members of the Central Electoral Commission are pleased to succeed.
Blood is safe again.
Yesterday, Hema-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its foundation. President Dr. Francine Décary had good reason to celebrate, because Hema-Québec has now become one of the safest and most effective blood donor companies in the world.
Most importantly, he managed to regain the trust of the people, which was severely shaken by the scandal of infected blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As it is known, the national blood reserve treated by the blood supply service of the Canadian Red Cross was infected with acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the drama and the general uproar, the Canadian government, led by Judge Horace Krever, launched an official investigation in February 1994 to shed light on the circumstances that led to the tragedy and to make proposals to avoid similar cases in the future.
While Judge Krever delayed submitting his report, some provinces set up their own committee to plan a new blood management system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee was responsible for this task.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two blood supply services were established in Canada: the Hema-Québec serving Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Supply Society responsible for the supply of all other provinces and the two territories.
“When Hema-Québec began operations in 1998, only 38% of people had confidence in Quebec’s blood system,” Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was desperate.
"In the following years, however, as a result of improving the safety of blood products and our work in the area, we managed to regain people's trust." Décary proudly states that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population considered Hema-Québec to be reliable.
However, Dr. Décary does not forget that "trust is an extremely fragile thing".
Since the foundation of Hema-Québec on 28 September 1998, it has applied the principle of caution.
During this period, a number of cases of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, were discovered in Europe, says the doctor, who has been managing the company since its foundation in 1998.
“We had no idea if this disease was transmitted by blood.
Therefore, we relied on one of the most important recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports. According to this, if we are uncertain about this and there is a risk of developing a serious disease, then we need to apply exclusion measures. In this case, we were talking about Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which causes brain damage and therefore inevitably leads to death.
Therefore, in April 1999, we did not accept blood from people who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
And a few years ago, there was no doubt that the disease was transmitted by blood.
This case convinced us that it made sense to apply the principle of caution."
In 1999, a technique was released on the market that allows for a much more sensitive diagnosis of HIV. This is the nucleic acid test (NAT), which is able to detect the virus itself directly in the blood of blood donors, rather than antibodies against the virus on which the previously used tests were built.
With the help of the NAT test, we were able to shorten the window period, which lasts from infection until we can detect the virus in the blood with the help of our technical tools, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, they significantly reduced the risk that blood donors unknowingly infect blood and that this could not be detected.
These developments have greatly reduced the risk of spreading AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, the risk of getting blood infected with HIV is 12 million to one.
In other words, we would have to distribute 12 million blood products until someone was infected with the HIV virus.
Since Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it would take more than 24 years for such a case to occur and for someone to be infected with HIV through a blood product.
I think anyone can now accept or prescribe a blood transfusion to restore health, says the number one leader of Hema-Québec.
“The challenge for the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
We never know what new pathogen will enter the system.
After all, it was only last year that the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, enters the blood with insect bites.
Therefore, we must be constantly on guard," continued Dr. Décary, and then stressed that apart from emergency reserves, Hema-Québec must provide sufficient permanent reserves.
“As the population ages, so does the demand.
Because anticancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need replacement of red blood cells or platelets.
Ageing of the population also affects the population of blood donors, as the number of people in the network who can donate blood accounts for only 3% of the Quebec population.
However, any healthy person at least 18 years of age who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of applicants do not accept blood because, for example, they are infected with AIDS or malaria, and those who have been to a country where malaria is devastating are not eligible to donate blood for a year.
“With this 3%, we have enough reserves to meet the needs of hospitals.
It's very rare for us to run out of supplies.
However, we need to increase the number of blood donors to the extent that the existing ones age, because after a while they can no longer donate blood.
However, it is very difficult to convince people to give blood, but it is even more difficult to keep them and make them become regular blood donors.
In today's rushing world, you barely have an hour to go and give blood," Francine Décary regrets.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeball tissues, and skin tissue, which is used almost exclusively for severely burned people.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen and then placed at Hema-Québec, which also manages Quebec’s only public stem cell bank.
The umbilical cord, once treated only as medical waste, can be extracted from blood rich in stem cells, so it can also be used to treat serious diseases (e.g. leukemia).
“We celebrated a few weeks ago that we included the 1,000th umbilical cord blood sample in our bank, and we plan to take more than a thousand new samples every year.
At the beginning of next year, we will probably start offering them for organ transplants," said Dr. Décary, who believes that the cord blood collection program is very popular today.
"Many mothers are sad that they don't have the opportunity to do so" - indeed, because Hema-Québec is not in a position to make this complex and costly program available in every hospital in Quebec.
