Charest's Northern Efforts
The Prime Minister does not rule out that the election will start this year.
As soon as the Liberal Party meeting was over, Jean Charest had already traveled to Jean-Talon, Quebec, where the new Minister of Health, Yves Bolduc (left) is seeking victory in the interim election to be held today.
"Repressing our last great northern border": this ambitious long-term goal was formulated by Jean Charest at yesterday's meeting of the Quebec Liberal Party in Lévis. The speech was enriched with visual elements, but at the same time the President tried to focus on the substance.
During his performance, behind his back, they projected images similar to "Moulin . images".
On the three giant projectors, stunning images followed: dams of hydroelectric power plants, mining, Quebec on "Google Maps", maps...
Such spectacular tools are used during election periods.
At the press conference, the Prime Minister refused to guarantee that the election would not start this autumn, although he added that his schedule was very tight.
The "Northern Plan" is the fourth pillar of the Prime Minister's "vision" of the future of Quebec, which is embodied in a "new economic area", which includes a labour agreement with France, an agreement between Canada and Europe and several agreements planned with Ontario.
Recently, the opening to the North (i.e. the northern area starting at latitude 49) has often been included in the Prime Minister's speeches, but he has never given a lecture on this subject.
However, the head of state merely explained why he considered the North to be "a treasure mine full of huge opportunities", but he did not mention the time factor, investment amounts, or specific priorities for future projects.
It highlighted only a few development opportunities: primarily hydroelectric power plants, forestry and, in particular, mining, which is further stimulated by the growth of catching-up countries and the reconstruction of public infrastructure.
In the north there is "nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium and even diamonds," said Charest.
This area, which is "twice the size of France", "is our territory, the territory of Quebec.
It is not only found in us, but in us," the head of state repeated, stressing that he wanted to create a national founding myth.
He pointed out that Quebec's development was largely determined by its relationship with the North: the gold rush in Abitibi, the design work in Quebec, the James Bay...
"This is ours, our future!" he added, after taking a stage break and looking at the huge map behind his back.
The North, which covers 70% of Quebec’s territory, includes part of Labrador, which Quebec has always demanded for itself, the Prime Minister said at the press conference.
“This is our historic resolution, which has been endorsed by all governments.
There is a line on which there has been no agreement for a long time, and if the opportunity arises, I will reconfirm the same resolution on behalf of the government," he said.
On the other hand, “we also need to rethink our view of the North in the light of climate change,” the Prime Minister said, speaking of the Northwest Passage that opens every year as the Arctic ice melts.
According to the Prime Minister, in this new geopolitical environment, the occupation of the territory is an important task.
And what about the natives of the area, the Indians and the Eskimos?
The Prime Minister said that the government of Quebec will pay special attention to them and that they will benefit a lot from the plan, especially young people.
The two ministers belonging to the different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (the latter was the delegate of the Parti Québécois inungava) have already started to consult with about 30 local communities.
The Interministerial Committee led by Beno’t Pelletier, in which Julie Boulet (Minister for Transport and Natural Resources) also plays an important role, has also started to operate.
The Prime Minister does not rule out the possibility of a large-scale meeting, “not necessarily a summit”, where “a common vision is being created”.
The development of the North would also take place in accordance with the principles of sustainable development.
The Northern Plan will be coordinated, systematic and at the same time environmentally friendly," the Prime Minister promised.
Jean Charest described this "vision" as in line with the ideas of the liberal prime ministers who preceded him.
“Just like the liberals of the past, we think differently: our goal is to create new opportunities for growth and development from challenges.”
This was one of the recurring themes of the weekend that began with the big cocktail party celebrating the 50th anniversary of Jean Lesage's election as party president on Friday.
One of the adopted decisions proposes that the Beauharnois power plant be renamed Adélard-Godbout dam.
“Our party’s politicians, including the Hydro-Québect founder Godbout, Lesage, who carried out the silent revolution and the national expansion of hydroelectric power plants, or Bourassa, known as the father of James Bay, all knew how to forge the future,” said Jean Charest.
At the press conference, he quoted another - true, conservative - work, namely John Diefenbaker, Prime Minister between 1957 and 1963, "Roads to the North".
Regarding the plan for the dam of the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydroelectric plant, President Charest pointed out that the plant was planned for 2012.
"This is between us, but I plan to be there," he told his followers, and his statement was greeted by a loud applause.
The Prime Minister, who said in April that there would be no election in 2008 and probably not in 2009, did not rule out the possibility of a vote to be held this autumn, which the law allows him to do.
However, he stressed that his calendar is already full, as he took on tasks at the Federal Council meeting in China and at the Quebec-New York summit.
The party assembly held at the end of the week proved to be an excellent platform for the liberal president to express nationalist decisions, which were approved almost without thinking. Here it is mainly about "constitutional aspirations": the liberal party in particular demands recognition of the "specific nature of Quebec" in the Constitution.
They also want Quebec to be able to appoint members of the Canadian Radio and Telecommunications Council, and these members would have a veto over the decisions taken in Quebec.
The opposition, on the other hand, was skeptical of the main points of the Northern Plan.
The leader of the Parti Québécois, Paulina Marois, once again raised the development policy in North Quebec, which was introduced by the Landry government in 2001.
According to Marois, the liberal government that came to power in 2003 refused to apply this policy.
If they had not done so, "we would have gone much further today," said Mrs Marois, in agreement with Mr Francoise Mercure, who was nominated for the Jean-Talon vote to be held today.
The opposition party ADQ supports the government's adoption of the Northern Plan.
“But we want this to be more than an act,” said Sébastien Proulx, who replaced Mario Dumont, who returned from his freedom today.
