Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In the September 17 issue of Le Devoir, a letter was published by Patrick J. Garver, Deputy Chairman and CEO of the Barrick Gold mine in Canada.
Following Orwelli's discussion, Garver states that the world's largest gold-producing company has filed a $6 million defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small-money publishing company in order to initiate a so-called "public debate".
Although judges are independent and impartial, their decision - especially in defamation lawsuits - is not based on the truth, but on the law.
It is not surprising that Garver was deeply silent about this fundamental difference.
Is the best way for Barrick Gold to have a public debate really to destroy anyone whose position is against his?
Regardless of the outcome of the lawsuit, the authors and publishers of the book Noir Canada will have to spend significant amounts of money on defense and fighting an unequal fight with an army of lawyers supported by almost inexhaustible resources from the mining industry on the other side.
In such an unequal struggle, by the way, the tactics are often used to destroy the defendant and make a friendly agreement, not only to silence the opposite, but even to intimidate those who would try to deal with the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have expressed its views in public.
Although in many other countries where Barrick Gold operates, this is different, in Canada the disputing parties do not usually hit each other with a stick, but tell their thoughts.
The mine would therefore have been enough to open its books and dossiers and prepare for a real debate in the press, media, publications, paying for independent research groups that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold doesn't seem to trust public opinion, and in one move, it sweeps away requests and letters to protect the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how he can initiate a "public" debate if, at the same time, he ignores the opinion of this public?
In the vice president's mind, this word probably only means well-paid lawyers, not the total population of Canada: the meaning of the concept is narrowed down.
In a democratic state, even those who disparage others are entitled to freedom of speech.
Barrick Gold, on the other hand, does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the authors and publishers of Noir Canada are mainly supported by the public because they condemn the harsh procedure of the mine.
The public is ready to listen to Barrick and make a judgment, but it would do so on the basis of civilized arguments, not through a trial for silence for many. (In connection with the term "public debate", Barrick Gold recently called on the authors of Noir Canada to refrain from using this term.)
In addition to Garver’s surrealism, Barrick Gold’s policy is an open attack on the freedom of academic research and the search for truth, which are the building blocks of every democratic society.
On the whole, the procedure denies the right to quote credible sources and to debate the facts and their interpretation, which are the basis for spiritual activities.
If, in a country like Canada, you can only study and discuss issues that do not appeal to the rich companies of today’s world, who will dare to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted an open and transparent debate, it could do so in accordance with the scientific standards applied by the authors of Noir Canada.
You have the right to respond.
In our university community, we have been able to deal with disputes, disagreements and conflicts for a long time.
Barrick Gold's ill-considered procedure shows that, contrary to its claim, it does not want to have an open debate.
This is a loss for both the world of universities and the institution of public debate in Canada. It is time for governments to finally put in place measures to restrict legal proceedings for this kind of abuse.
Wall Street Rescue: Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Republican and Democratic leaders of the Bush administration and Congress finally reached an agreement yesterday on the economic rescue operation, which is the largest such plan since the Great Depression in the 1930s.
The $700 billion plan, which aims to contain the financial crisis that has been raging on Wall Street for months, still needs to be approved by the two houses of Congress.
The main points of the plan are: more effective monitoring of implementation by Members; new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the public funds envisaged; new provisions to maintain the number of houses booked for non-payment; access to the salaries of the managers of the companies receiving assistance.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, U.S. House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican Congressman Judd Gregg announced the good news yesterday, a few minutes before midnight, after the two-day marathon trial ended.
“We have made great progress towards a solution that will work effectively in the markets,” said Henry Paulson, a representative for the Bush administration.
“We did everything we could to save the real economy and American citizens from the current crisis on Wall Street,” he said.
“The most important aspect is that if we don’t do that, there will be a tremendous amount of shock, chaos and confusion in the daily lives of Americans,” said Judd Gregg.
The trial has been accelerated in the last few hours, fearing that another failure would have a detrimental effect on investors' moods.
They gave themselves a deadline for the deal until the stock exchange opened this morning.
The two presidential candidates who joined the negotiations late showed willingness to reach an agreement, however, they expressed that they were not happy that the situation had increased to the end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama attributed to himself the extension of the agreement with elements such as provisions on the preservation of house ownership or the payment of heads of state-assisted companies.
“When we ask taxpayers to take extraordinary steps to address other people’s irresponsibility, that’s not very welcome.
These steps, however, are necessary," he said on an American television show.
And when his opponent, John McCain, was asked by another network if he would vote in favour of the proposed plan, he replied: "I would like to know the details, but I hope so."
“What I have read in broad outline is that it is something that we all have to digest and by which we can move on.
The possibility of doing nothing is simply unacceptable,” he said.
According to the $700 billion plan, taxpayers would use their money to buy the dubious demands of American financial institutions, something at risk, unsellable.
The plan was preceded by a 14-month crisis triggered by the bursting of real estate balloons. This first led to the collapse of risky real estate loans (secondary mortgage loans), then spread to other debt (commercial) securities, and finally caused the freezing of liquid resources and the uproar of banks and financial institutions.
The first draft deal was defeated by a group of Republican MPs last week.
We seem to have gotten out of this dead end since the Democrats agreed that some of the "toxic" tools of companies in difficulty should be provided by the government rather than bought up.
In order for all members of Congress to be satisfied, the plan included a provision requiring that if the government had to bear losses under the program for five years, it could impose new taxes to recover its resources.
As part of the new plan, a $250 billion installment would be paid first; an additional $100 billion could follow if the president deems it necessary.
The remaining $350 billion should be approved by Congress by a new vote.
In exchange for the help, Washington acquires a stake in the supported companies, through which it receives dividends from the profits and can sell them after the crisis has come to an end.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay the seizure of the property to cover the mortgages covered by the plan. It can also set the maximum value of the salary and severance pay that can be paid to the managers of companies affected by the crisis.
The drafters of the plan would like the plan to be voted on today by the House of Representatives and Wednesday by the Senate.
Despite their efforts, however, it is still not certain that the plan will be approved.
There have been repeated objections to the plan by both Republicans and Democrats.
“It is absolutely clear that Washington cannot hear your voice,” Scott Garrett, a Republican member of the House Finance Committee, told voters.
“We have serious financial problems.
Yes, there are solutions.
But there is nothing that would benefit the taxpayers.”
Brad Sherman, the Democratic leader of the small congressional group called the "sceptic faction", presents things differently, but he comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred eminent economists, including three Nobel Prize-winning scientists, have written to us asking Congress not to hurry and to look carefully at which path it chooses,” Sherman said.
At the same moment in Europe, it was once again understood that this was a global crisis.
Following a crisis meeting, the three Benelux states announced that they would nationalise part of the Fortis banking group worth EUR 11.2 billion (16.3 billion US dollars).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg was necessary after the French BNP Paribas announced that it would not buy up its on the verge of bankruptcy after losing EUR 2 million (US$ 2,9 billion) as a result of the crisis of subprime mortgages in the United States.
With 85,000 employees, Fortis is one of the 20 largest banks in Europe and one of the 10 largest insurance companies.
“This is not wasted money,” Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
"We will gain voting rights and influence in the bank.
This is exactly what depositors and households appreciate now that the situation promises to be uncertain."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the English Manche, the British government seems to be about to nationalize another bank that has been swept away by the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over the sum of the ongoing loans of Bradford and Bringley bank, of which real estate loans amount to 41 billion pounds (75.5 billion US dollars).
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it will acquire the British bank’s subsidiaries and client holdings.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank after Northern Rock that the British government has wanted to nationalise since the beginning of the crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Farewell to the Idol
Some say his beautiful azure eyes were his main trump card, others say his main weakness.
Did the American actor with a charming smile ever get rid of his narcissist mirror?
Yes and no.
Through his shyness, sensitivity, and innate talent, he was also far from the loud style that is the essence of the true great monsters of the art world.
But what a great career he's had!
Paul Newman died of lung cancer at the age of 83 on Friday at his Connecticut estate, one of the last icons of the American cinema boom.
He was less monumental than Brando, whom he resembled, and who for a long time was a rival on the screen. In his roles he was more restrained and undoubtedly more vulnerable, but he also proclaimed freedom and the destruction of dramatic conventions.
The mixing of blood often results in extraordinary children.
Newman was born in 1925 in Ohio as a child of a German Jewish father and a mother of Hungarian origin.
European roots contributed to the birth of a symbolic figure of the American dream.
He didn't think much of himself, which only increased his merits.
In the early 1950s, he studied drama at Yale University and then at Actor's Studio in New York, before bursting into the world of theatre, television and shortly thereafter cinema.
In addition to being at the forefront of civil rights, he won second place in the Le Mans 24-hour race in 1979 as a racing driver. He was also considered a sex symbol, although he had been happily married to actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
Now we'll never know the downsides of this mysterious, private, dedicated actor who hated the glamour of show business, which will forever remain a mystery.
He was an honest man, in the most noble sense of the word.
Paul Newman's death at the end of the week shocked movie fans: in his great roles we can only see him on the black screen of memories.
Looking through his oeuvre, we have seen the seventh American art, cinema with continuous changes for more than 50 years.
In our memory, the charming cowboy of "Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid" (1969) and the estranged young man from his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor), whose role was seen in the Tennessee Williams processing of "Cat on the Hot Tin Roof" in 1958.
Recently (1990) we can remember him in the form of the sensitive Mr. Bridge, who, in his old age, faces the fact that his marriage has not fulfilled his hopes.
Paul Newman also had many other faces in his films.
In Robert Wise's film "Someone Up There", he performed an unforgettable performance in the role of stormy criminal boxer Rocky Graziano. This role originally intended for James Dean - and taken over after his death - started Newman's acting career in 1956.
He also played a sympathetic criminal in a brilliant work called "The Big Trouble", which won the Oscar for the best film in 1973.
Robert Rossen played a bitter, vengeful billiard player in his brilliant film "The Swindler" (1961) and returned in a similar role in Martin Scorsese's film "The Color of Money".
Times have changed, but it's always the same face: it was him.
He's always been like this.
The period of his career was marked by a change in ages.
Younger people know him mainly from George Roy Hill's cult film "Icebreakers" (1977), where he plays Reggie Dunlop, a coach of a hockey team with unconventional methods.
His fans saw him in the Coen brothers' "The Great Jump" in 1994.
The line was closed by Sam Mendes' film "The Way of Damnation" in 2003, which was the last to appear in the role of an Irish mob boss.
Unlike many movie legends who left the screen relatively soon, Newman remained in the spotlight for a long time, although he condemned Hollywood with its glamour, luxury, and hypocrisy.
French film director Bertrand Tavernier did not view it as "a living rebuttal of underplaying" without humor: he thought his game was too powerful.
However, the profession was not always gracious to the handsome Paul Newman, whose film roles fell into his lap for a long time.
Yet he played young and successful characters less often: rather, he formed figures on the edge of society - neurotic, alcoholic, malignant or hopeless - whose drift and rebellion he was able to restore with perfect credibility.
As a director, he showed a less known face of Newman: deep down, he was a really chaste and sensitive man.
In the 1968 film "Rachel, Rachel" (adaptation of the novel by Canadian writer Margaret Laurence), she starred in a fine portrait of a melancholy woman with her wife Joanne Woodward.
And with the film "Harry and Son" made in 1984, he commemorates his son Scott, who died of a drug overdose.
Yesterday, many of Newman's admirers remembered the actor. His close friend and old warrior Robert Redford (with whom they played together in "The Great Trouble" and "Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid") said with sorrow: "His presence has made my life and the world better.
Generosity and the joy of being: that was the secret of the vibrant personality of this great actor that we have now lost.
In addition to his legendary career, his comments on civil rights, the environment, the struggle for independent film production and Hollywood's debauchery are obscured.
We could see his face smiling on the packaging of sauces, sauces, biscuits and other foods. He did it with a bad taste in his mouth, although at the beginning he thought it was funny.
However, the proceeds from such sales were always transferred to the foundation for children suffering from the disease.
Newman never sat on his laurels: he remained committed to the profession all along.
In his letter to his five daughters, he wrote the following sentences: "Your father was always and always unimaginably grateful for his lucky star.
It was a privilege for me to be here.”
It is also a privilege for us to be able to accompany the career of such a brilliant and generous American artist.
He was a model citizen, above all.
What was produced at Zuschlag & Tsai's account factory?
Soon, on 8 October, the trial of János Zuschlag and his associates will begin.
The politician and his associates are accused of fraud and other crimes, including forgery, which cause particularly significant damage to a criminal organisation.
According to the prosecution, the funds received were used for their own purposes, and the performance of the tasks was often confirmed by false invoices.
State and municipal money - about HUF 65 million in total - has migrated partly into the cash register of the Young Left and partly into the pockets of some people.
The method also described by the investigating authority was that the tender money obtained was taken on the basis of cost accounts that were not behind real performance, and the associations never fulfilled the commitment they had undertaken.
According to the indictment, most of the accounts were fake.
For these, the account blocks were purchased on the Józsefváros market, and the circular stamps were manufactured in Kiskunhala.
And the names of which companies to produce invoices were decided, among other things, on the Balaton-felvidéki körút to which János Zuschlag sent István Lados.
According to the latter's testimony, he had to look like boarding houses and restaurants.
He asked for an invoice for his consumption there, the model of which was then prepared for the applications of the Ministry of Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour and the Municipality of Budapest.
Most of these were written by István Lados with his partner András Őri, who, according to our information, wrote mostly the reports needed to obtain the grants.
One of Lados's "study trips" was a beer house.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlags, dated 2003, the restaurant provided food for the 90-person group of the Sure Point Association.
However, according to the manager, they would not have been able to fit into the restaurant at the same time.
Similarly, the invoice issued to the Foundation for a Better Future - later Together for the Third Millennium - in the summer of 2002 was full of errors in form and content.
A pension in Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms, more than ten people could not sleep in it one night, yet the bill was about a hundred and thirty guests.
But the imaginative form fillers also went too far when they marked Pigal Kft., which is also a catering company, whose accounts - according to the information given to the prosecution - did not even include documents for the Better Future and the name of the Oops.
The head of the company, Győző Farkas, told hvg.hu that when he was called to the D.A.'s office and bills were shown to him, he knew immediately that it was false documents.
"Our business name and tax number were in the wrong place on the stamp."
He added that in addition to the formal reasons, it was not right that a hundred people were accommodated according to the account, as they have a total of eleven rooms in which there are not so many seats.
In addition, the bill was for catering, while their restaurant had long since ceased to work.
The zealous account makers did not even look into the fact that the Budapest travel agency they looked at only organizes trips abroad, so they indicated a trip to Hungary as a service on the cash payment account, which also did not match the company's account issuing practice.
In addition, as the investigation revealed, VAT was also included on the document, even though travel activities to countries outside the European Union were VAT-free.
Among other things, the VAT rate was wrong on the four documents issued by Hotel Révfülöp Kft. for the Better Future, as the company's service is not subject to the indicated 25 percent VAT, but to 15 percent VAT, and the hotel's employees only issued a machine invoice, but the invoice produced was manual.
In addition, the "exhibitors" also ruined the account by indicating road freight transport as an activity carried out in the case of a company, as revealed by the prosecution procedure, which was not carried out by the company based on investment advice.
In addition, it was also due to formal differences - not the right account format, not a real stamp - that the accounts for the Together for the Third Millennium Foundation, the 21st century Cultural Association and the Commissioner Point were false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or Kunfehértó Sport Camp, whose representatives denied that the accounts had been issued by them.
For example, the forgers did not pay attention to the fact that HIB Kft. in Nyíregyháza was in liquidation at the time (2001) when the group of the Young City Association ate there, which is why the company's liquidator denied, as far as we know, that he had issued the paper.
Consciously put out
Another group of account issuers are those who were aware that they had to issue a fictitious account.
At the request of the Young Left - Young Socialists, the Chance for Budapest Foundation issued an invoice for the Foundation for the Third Millennium for some HUF 4 million.
According to the indictment, the head of Collab Kft. was persuaded by one of the defendants, Györfi Ludovic, to issue the fictitious account.
Biogate Kft., currently in liquidation, also cooperated with the Zuschlags, which in 2003 provided the Foundation for a Better Future, the Atlas Association and the Redwood Association with invoices for roughly HUF 5 million, behind which there was no real economic activity.
Nor is it a movement of money, because the completed invoices were then downloaded, but this has already been forgotten by the organisations in their documents.
The next group of companies issuing invoices are those that can be linked to the defendants.
Thus, Iván Kubatov was the delivery agent of the Ukrainian Managing Director of Delta Trió Kft., based in Budapest.
The company issued several invoices for the sale of computer devices in October, November and December 2005, worth about HUF 18 million.
According to the data of the investigation, these accounts were purchased by Cash Investment Kft. in Kiskunhalas, which has been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The managing director of this company was a Romanian man to whom Iván Kubatov would also have forwarded the documents related to the company between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov admitted in the course of the investigation that he issued an invoice on behalf of the Ltd. to Atlas, Oops and the Together for the Third Millennium Foundation, and took up their consideration.
At the request of Iván Kubatov, Romanian masons founded Fa-Bani Jos Fapari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
However, none of the companies actually worked, which, according to the defendant, was because they didn't get a job.
However, the companies benefited because, at the request of Zsolt Szente, his fellow defendant, who also prepared the company's founding documents, he issued invoices on behalf of the companies to associations related to Zuschlag: Atlas and Y-Generation.
On behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trio, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, Kubatov gave 15 accounts to organizations worth HUF 14.2 million.
According to the prosecutor, 10 percent of the amounts on the invoices and the VAT hit Kubatov's hand.
The man even used Szi-Beri Bt. to issue fictitious invoices, which were manufactured for the application of the Commissioner Point.
In January 2006, the Y-Generation and the Association for Modern Hungary submitted an application to the Socialist Party's public benefit organization, the Táncsics Mihály Foundation (TMA).
They also won 500-500 thousand forints, but the amounts were not used for the purposes indicated in the tender.
In order not to reveal this, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft. were submitted to TMA.
These bills were found, by the way, during the search at Árpád Kemecsei's office at the education wallet.
At the trial, some of the defendants, as they did at the D.A.'s office, are likely to report on the progress of the account production.
Most interestingly, if you are the primary defendant, János Zuschlag decides to lift the veil on everything.
His testimony so far is not very detailed, and although he has repeatedly promised to talk about everything, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest, or whether the socialists made a deal with him for the reimbursement of most of the damage, 50 million forints, and Zusi takes the fall.
By the way, he may have been offended today, since his requests to alleviate the circumstances of his detention, i.e. to put him under house arrest, were constantly on deaf ears.
While the perpetrators of economic crimes that cause much more damage and do not compensate for it can walk freely or at least wait for the end of the proceedings against them in their own homes, he does not have the opportunity to do so.
The psychology of overbiding: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more money, overvalue the goods.
The neurological-economic foundations of this known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been explored by neurologists and economists at the University of New York.
According to a study published in the journal Science, people do not want to be left behind in a type of competition such as eBay auction, so they prefer to pay too high a price.
The research tried to map the nervous system pattern of this "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery and the other group took part in a player auction while using the functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) method to examine the active brain areas of the subjects.
In both games, participants could win money, but during the auction game, in which the essential element is the overbiding of the other party, the complex under the cerebral cortex called striatum was intensively activated when the game was lost.
This brain area plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system, among other functions.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price can be explained by avoiding the violent reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the economists of the research group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this, three groups bid against a partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made their bets.
Another group was also promised that if they came out of the game winning, they would be rewarded with $15 more.
The third group, on the other hand, received $15 just before the auction, but in the event of a losing auction, the members of the group also lost this money.
The only difference between the two groups was that they emphasized winning for one and losing for the other.
However, by proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the "lost" team were willing to bet even higher than the control and "winner" groups.
“These results cannot be derived from any pre-existing economic theory.
So far, they have only explained the phenomena of the auction with the joy of victory and risk aversion.
Only neurological imaging methods helped to resolve the discrepancy between these two theories, and now we have a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, a professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
About half a billion people around the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is one of the leading causes of death.
There are 100,000 people infected with hepatitis at home, but only 7,000 are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a collective name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, characteristic of hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and diseases are different.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the pathogen, spread in two main forms: hepatitis A and E through the gastrointestinal tract (e.g. infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (dono, vaginal secretions, saliva).
Travelers should definitely be vaccinated against viruses A and B, there is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected food, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal complaint, nausea.
After that, the jaundice on the skin and whites of the eyes develops, the stool becomes light, the urine becomes dark, and the healing can take two to three weeks.
One million people worldwide die each year from more severe forms of the disease, liver cancer and cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people receive medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver, liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, because the pathogen insidiously destroys liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms occur only 20-30 years later.
Thus, it is very important to perform early prevention and regular screening tests.
There are many more cases in three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users, and tattooed people.
There are currently 200 million people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus in the world.
Since the disease can already be detected by a routine laboratory test, it is worth contacting your GP when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognizing in time, the disease can be cured, the virus can be eradicated from the body, thus eliminating infectivity and preventing the development of cancer.
30 September is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organisations representing patients around the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early detection of the disease.
If you believe in God, does it hurt less?
According to a recent study, religious faith acts as a kind of painkiller that could have made it easier for Catholic martyrs to die.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment to investigate how belief in God affects people's perception of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
As part of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were given electroshock while they were all studying a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of the pain.
Thanks to the technique of scanning the human brain, it was also found that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for controlling pain.
The study is the first in a series of research involving academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university.
The study was conducted by attaching a sparking device to the left hand of the subject, which provided the electroshock.
Researchers asked those involved in the experiment to look hard at two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and Leonardo da Vinci’s painting Lady with Hermelin in the 15th century.
The authors of the study hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would cause a kind of religious state among believers, while the da Vinci picture was chosen because it was not too different from the other and was thought to be soothing.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, during which time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive parts while looking at either the religious theme or the general picture.
Catholics reported that when they saw the Virgin Mary, they felt "safe" as they "kept taking care of" and "rested, filled with peace".
When looking at the religious picture, they reported 12% less pain than when they saw Leonardo's work in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the study himself, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any strong image, including atheists, only the right photo needs to be found.
“We should find a picture of someone who feels very positively, like a mother or a father,” the psychologist said.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
“The practice of faith should, and in many cases will, change our personality,” Wright said.
After the great results, the only question is, if Leonardo or a painter of similar caliber were to show the believers a picture of a madonna, how would that affect their pain control?
Would seeing the quality of the Virgin Mary mean even better results?
You are what you share about yourself
On his tenth birthday, Google can say that people have it in their pockets as much as they have it above their heads in the sky; he knows where they vacationed, what specialties they go to and what they are interested in.
That’s not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company’s top executives.
As for the skeptics who draw parallels with the Orwellian horror, they do not see the essence of web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main goal is to collect more personal data about their users, which is necessary to be able to adhere to the original goal of Google founders, which was to "collect all the information in the world!"
According to Google, after ten years of world-changing work, the company is only at the beginning of being able to handle all the information.
Asked what would happen in five years, Schmidt said he wanted Google to be able to answer questions like “what should I do tomorrow?” or “what kind of work would really suit me?” but until then, software could not answer questions that seemed so simple because they didn’t know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that search engines are accurately recorded in Internet searches, which IP address they were searched from and which page the interested parties left after the search.
For example, Personalized Search, launched two years ago, allows users to store their own surfing background, look back at what they were looking for and clicked on, and generate much more personalized results for them in the long run - the same logic will be used by Recommendations to offer us products and services based on our previously mentioned and recorded preferences.
What if they use my data against me when they look at what I do? – users who are concerned about Google’s data monopoly ask.
In most cases, the amount of potential power represented by the company can be frightening, not the fear of guilt, the fear of punishment, the desire for freedom, or the rebellion against power in Internet users.
However, it is confirmed that all search terms are not only recorded, but may also be handed over to third parties in justified cases, and in such cases the privacy rights of Internet users are not protected.
Perhaps the loudest example of this in recent times was the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, in which Google provided the Brazilian government with information about pedophiles on the social network Orkut, which it maintains.
However, Internet users concerned about privacy rights may have sighed in May when the company, in cooperation with the EFF electronic rights organization, successfully proved its truth in court against the FBI: Google cannot be forced to provide any information requested by the FBI in secret.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully fought off some 50,000 web addresses and thousands of search terms by referring to the strengthening of the child protection law adopted years earlier, but failed to obtain the search lists of individual users and the full list of websites and keywords covering two months.)
So Google's view is rather controversial: it is being flogged by those who fear to provide their personal data because they feel that their intimacy and privacy are being undermined by the fact that they are starting to use Google's services and are acting against them by rebelling against the multi-company in a conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users in many countries see in them the next generation of big companies, the "cool corporation", as opposed to its rival Microsoft, who has been declared world conqueror because of Windows, no matter how much they both struggle for the same goal.
This may happen because Google does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask for money for its applications, the open, free, continuously kept source code and program package seems much more accessible, youthful, cooler than the official software giant practice.
However, it may also happen that geeks have a clear understanding of the very problematic relationship between personality rights and the Internet, which was followed by one of the most frequently spoken keywords in recent years, the web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about collaboration, about deliberately leaving clues and exploiting the communication channels available to us, and while these vary from person to person, the point is the same: we show ourselves.
The average young person can lead a profile from Facebook to Xanga on several social media sites, connect them to other services such as Twitter or last.fm listing their musical habits, and then connect them all to tracking systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, and also lead a blog with their latest photo galleries automatically displayed on Flickr or Pic.
While we can read about a number of exemplary cases from which it is clear: a girlfriend can easily find out who her cheating friend spent the evening with or can fire a company employee just because he writes his honest opinion on senior management in his blog: one thing is certain, the concept of privacy has been completely re-evaluated by now.
If you live an online life, it consists of what you show yourself, this is how we can formulate the basic principle behind the behavior of today's young people.
And anyone who wants to hide something or at least avoid the Google monopoly can do so (starting with Scroogle using Google's search system but deliberately leaving no trace).
For example, the number of people who deliberately do not register on social networks so that they cannot be found, Google's online applications can be replaced from word processor to image manager and news reader with alternative versions that do not connect to huge server parks and that do not create the best profile that has ever existed.
The public is not so secretive about when Google will show its teeth.
With its current value of $156 billion, the company is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising platforms threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, and the services introduced at an accelerating pace cause severe headaches not only for Microsoft but also for many other software developers.
However, critical observers also find these disturbing counterpoints: for example, the senior management completely rejected the protests of the employees after doubling the fee of the company kindergarten, the management found it too expensive to feed the employees on a daily basis, but all of this is dwarfed by the fact that in 2006 Google bowed to the Chinese government and, according to their agreement, the company filters out all the hits that violate the interests of the good taste.
One of the company's internal rules is that they don't announce a new service until it's ready for use, but it's certain that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years can move the world at another point: while some believe that Google's book and magazine scanning and archiving project is on such a scale that the company will soon face the U.S. Supreme Court, others are afraid of our previous health system, and we are afraid of our own health system.
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database can also give good material to the next generation of sci-fi writers, the popular Cory Doctorow novel, Scroogled, describes the future in which a person can only be approached alarmingly well from Google's data.
Two juveniles helped the Osdi double killer with the disappearance of the trail
