The flying of the bumblebee is imitated by the intelligent car
What would be the best way to develop technologies to avoid collisions if not to imitate obstacle sensors in the natural world?
The bees, for example.
In the surprising project presented at the CEATEC in Japan, the bumblebee bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic idea of how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C type bioimitation car robot control system, a robotic minicar equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the ultimate goal of facilitating the development of a system that eliminates all collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval-shaped personal space, which is in fact very similar to our safety barrier,” explained Kazuhhiro Doi, Chief Technology Officer for PR and R&D at the exhibition.
An important role is played by the complex eye of the uterus, which can see in all directions at an angle of view of more than 300 degrees.
To copy its complex eye function, engineers touched on the idea of a laser telescope.
This identifies obstacles within a distance of 2 metres in front of the BR23C, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately converted into an action to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second, the obstacle is detected, and then the car robot, imitating the movements of the uterus, immediately changes direction by turning its wheels to the extent necessary to avoid a collision.
Unlike any current system, this avoidance maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If that were not the case, the car-robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car-robot project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and inner layer of the safety barrier, a layer within which a collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does in order to avoid other bees.
This process should take place in the blink of an eye.
However, other than bees, the deviation cannot be directed upwards, downwards, or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the turnability of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the endless possibility for bees to avoid other bees, only rotating movement and acceleration and deceleration were used as an available option for the car robot.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means that they have a longer service life than the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, instinctive intelligent reaction is important, not the ability to process data, even less to store it.
This device only needs to process and respond to a few input signals per second.
There is no need to preserve them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so you are constantly using only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
There is no need for gigabytes or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of immediate-emergency technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production cars within ten years.
An additional application can be the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to the specified destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
