A written version of the $700 billion economic rescue package law to be applied in several instalments to buy bad loans from banks has been drawn up.
In the first round, half the amount is spent.
During the recent talks that took place after midnight on Saturday, congressional leaders came to an agreement in the days-long debate around a total of $700 billion in bailouts, Reuters reported.
“We have made significant progress,” said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic president of the House of Representatives, who said that the deal is now on paper.
The compromise on the package was supported by both presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain.
Commenting on the outcome of the compromise, Finance Minister Henry Paulson said that the programme will work and be effective, but further work is needed. Pelosi said that this is not about saving Wall Street, but about turning the economy around.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of the Asian markets on Sunday evening at 8 p.m. (i.e. Monday at 2 a.m. Central European time), but did not cause a spectacular rise in the fairs.
The draft legislation on the programme, which is called the 2008 Economic Emergency Stabilisation Act, will be voted on by the House of Representatives on Monday and then by the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke with Pelosi on Saturday evening, and the White House welcomed the news of the agreement.
“We are pleased with the progress made last night and appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy,” White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
The program differs from the Bush administration’s original proposal to spend $700 billion on low-quality, credit-backed securities.
Now, for the first time, up to half of the $700 billion can be spent by using $250 billion immediately after Congress is expected to vote on the matter on Monday, from which the Treasury Department buys credit-backed, poor-rated securities, and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the President's decision.
The program will be monitored by a separate body, which will include the chairman of the Federal Reserve.
The spending of the other half of the 700 billion depends on a new resolution by Congress.
Under the law, the Ministry of Finance can use a combination of tactics: you can buy bad loans, mortgages and mortgage-backed securities at the same time, as well as other types of "toxic" loans.
The purchase can be made directly and through auctions, the ministry said.
The legislation allows the companies concerned to participate in an insurance programme where the financial portfolio guarantees the assets of concern, for which companies will pay a fee corresponding to the expected damage.
Henry Paulson said the law provides the necessary means to provide up to $700 billion to meet the urgent needs of the U.S. financial system, whether it is a widespread purchase of bad assets, insurance, or avoiding systemic risk associated with the collapse of a large financial institution.
We will take the necessary steps to be ready to introduce the law as soon as it is signed, he added.
However, bosses of banks in distress and waiting for state help can expect their exit money, which the overseas slang simply calls a golden parachute, to be limited by the government.
Payments are restricted only in certain cases, and the limits depend on the way in which the Ministry of Finance provides assistance.
The restriction essentially means that if the Ministry buys under an auction, an additional tax will be levied on the gold parachute unless the retired bank manager is retired.
When buying bad loans directly, the government will aggressively intervene to ensure that management money is not exaggerated.
Part of the picture is that existing gold parachute contracts do not change, the restriction applies only to new ones to encourage participation in the program.
This is the first time in American history that there will be a legal restriction on the remuneration of CEOs, said House Financial Services Committee Chairman Barney Frank of the Democratic Party.
In addition, in the banks participating in the programme, the State acquires the right to acquire shares, thus reducing the risk for taxpayers, as they can eventually win the transaction as the economy and the bank saved with it recovers.
In the next five years, the president will have to submit to Congress a proposal on how to return the expected losses to taxpayers from the financial sector.
Of course, there were those on both sides who expressed doubts about the plan.
“This is not what the American people asked us to do, which is not to protect taxpayers’ dollars,” said Darrell Issa, a Republican from California.
His Ohio Democrat colleague Mary Kaptur said the measures were being urged by the same people responsible for Wall Street’s collapse.
Industrial prices continue to rise
The domestic sales prices of the industry increased by 0.1 percent in August 2008 compared to the previous month and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007, the HCSO reports.
The prices of industrial export sales were 1.1 percent higher than in July 2008, decreasing by 3.9 percent compared to a year earlier.
As a result of domestic and export price changes, industrial producer prices were 0.7% higher than in the previous month and 3.2% higher than in the previous year.
Domestic sales prices of the industry increased only minimally, by 0,1 % compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing sector also increased slightly, by 0.1% compared to July.
The largest price increase occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 percent), mainly due to a 4.6 percent increase in the production of bags and belts and a 2.5 percent increase in the production of footwear.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical and product manufacturing sector (1.6%).
There was a decrease in prices in the oil processing (1.4 percent), the production of electric machines and instruments (0.9 percent) and, to a minimum, wood processing (0.1 percent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In the other manufacturing sectors, a price increase of between 0.2% and 0.9% was measured.
In August, prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector, which has a significant weight in domestic sales of industry, increased by 0.3 percent, mainly due to the transitory effect of the official gas price increase from 1 July.
Compared to 12 months of domestic sales in the manufacturing sector, prices increased the most in the petroleum processing sector (32.4%).
In the metalworking sector, a price increase of 13.2% was observed in the field of food, drink and tobacco production, representing a dominant weight of 11 percent.
Price reductions occurred in the textile and textile production (2.5 percent) and in the electrical machinery and instrument production (0.3 percent) sectors.
In the other manufacturing sectors, the rate of price increase was between 0.6% and 9.1%.
In the manufacturing industry as a whole, prices have increased by 10.2% over the past year.
Electricity, gas, steam and water prices were 18.7% higher than a year earlier.
In August, the sectors producing capital goods showed the highest monthly price increases (0.7%) among the intended groups of sectors in domestic sales.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices have increased by 0.3%, and in the energy and re-use sectors prices have not changed compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, the largest price increase compared to the same month of the previous year was observed in the energy and re-use sectors (16.8%).
In the consumer goods sectors, we measured a price increase of 6.8 percent and a price decrease of 1.4 percent for capital goods.
Export sales prices of the industry in HUF increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, and decreased by 3.9 percent in 12 months.
In one month, our domestic currency weakened by 1.7 percent compared to the euro and 7.1% compared to the dollar, increasing by 7.5 percent compared to the euro and 15.9 percent compared to the dollar.
