Járóka: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today, the European Equal Opportunities Summit began in Paris, hosted this year by France, representing the Presidency of the European Union.
Lívia Járóka, Fidesz MEP of the European People's Party, in her message to the plenum as one of the main speakers of the professional meeting, drew attention to educational segregation, because this is one of the most serious violations affecting Roma children and, moreover, this is the most serious obstacle to their enforcement.
The high-level conference was opened by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities, on behalf of the French Presidency.
Among those invited to the meeting were representatives of governments, the European social partners and the most important European human rights defenders and civil society organisations in the field of equal opportunities.
Járóka, according to the press office of the Fidesz EP Group, warned that, in addition to discrimination in recruitment, Roma are excluded from the labour market primarily because of their low level of education.
"The vast majority of Roma young people do not have secondary education, and as a result of poor quality primary education, only a small part of them can obtain higher education".
Járóka also stressed that, as a fundamental human right, education plays a key role in the enforcement of other human rights.
Investing in early education for Roma children can strengthen the economies of the EU Member States.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these links to the widest extent, including between Roma and non-Roma.
As soon as the Roma student starts school, his chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market increase; they contribute to the national budget through taxes on income and consumption.
“Roma must be guaranteed the right to quality education on the basis of their EU citizenship and must be guaranteed the elimination of their low-quality and separate education,” said Lívia Járóka.
According to the MEP, the goal and action-oriented cooperation of the European Union is necessary to speed up the desegregation processes in schools, and the correct enforcement of existing and planned anti-discrimination directives is essential for this.
“The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be broken, and Roma children must be given the opportunities offered by the democratic space to contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens”, Járóka demanded.
As part of the European Year of Equal Opportunities for All, the European Equal Opportunities Summit, which has been held annually since last year in Berlin, aims to provide a unique forum for promoting the goals of equal opportunities and non-discrimination at European and national level.
