MP3 players can cause hearing damage
Permanent hearing loss can be caused by listening to portable player devices for a longer period of time and at a high volume level, such as MP3 devices.
In a report published in Brussels today, the European Commission, the EU’s Scientific Committee on New and Newly Identified Health Risks (SCENIHR), said in a statement.
“The report shows that 5-10 percent of people who listen to their portable music players at high volume for more than an hour a day for five years may suffer permanent hearing loss,” the report said.
“It is worrying that young people who use high volume portable music players and mobile phones on a massive and frequent basis are not aware that they can irreversibly damage their hearing,” Kuneva said.
“Scientific assessments indicate an indisputable risk that we urgently need to respond to,” he said.
The most important task is to inform consumers and to disseminate information on this.
In the light of this opinion, we also need to review the existing control systems so that they can operate efficiently and keep up with the latest technologies".
Brussels asked the independent scientific committee to look into the problem in view of the prevalence of portable music players and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they cause.
"The researchers confirm that there is cause for concern, and the European Commission, in cooperation with Member States and stakeholders, is ready to explore possible measures to protect children and young people who are exposed to noise from portable players and similar devices," he said.
The current European safety standard defines the maximum noise level that can be emitted by portable music players at 100 dB, but there is increasing concern about data on hearing loss resulting from the excessive use of such sound sources.
At the same time, there are solutions, such as reducing the level and duration of noise pollution, that can significantly reduce these hearing impairments.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee explains that for users who listen to music at high volume levels (more than 89 decibels) for five hours a week, noise pollution exceeds the current maximum level for noise at work.
If you listen to music for a long time under similar conditions, there is a risk of permanent hearing loss after five years.
This affects about 5-10% of portable device users, which could mean 2.5-10 million people in the EU.
