The elite is in danger.
The phenomenon was felt a few days ago when the House of Representatives did not vote for the $700 billion rescue package tabled by the White House: a significant part of Americans were more interested and still interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
This is supported by yesterday’s New York Times, which informs us that the current crisis has created a rift within the Republican Party, which is increasingly divided between the traditional, restrained East Coast attitude that supports federal institutions and business circles and the growing new trend against Washington and the financial world in the Central and Southern States.
This line was expressed in a critical way during the House vote mentioned in the introduction.
However, the above event is only one of the major changes that the economic rearrangement that is still taking place predicts or allows to be seen, not only in the United States, but throughout the Western world and perhaps even beyond.
It seems that the crisis, both in the US and in Europe, is only accelerating the long-delayed phenomena that have been solidified in this new atmosphere and are finally coming to light.
The first such phenomenon is the redeployment, the return of the dual category of state sovereignty to the public consciousness, in connection with a kind of renationalisation of the economy.
Indeed, the crisis affects banking and financial institutions that, although having a close relationship with the rest of the world, primarily and quite widely, carry with them people and families who live in one country, one state.
This, in turn, is a direct political difficulty for those in government: how should they respond to the difficulties and protests of people who are also voters?
So the crisis seems to be worldwide in economic terms, but in political terms it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to be essentially out of line: the European Union, which is unable to set a unified political direction between different interests and different national strategies, is an eloquent proof of this.
Thus, everyone expects the intervention, the rescue package, the recovery and the new rules, but above all the opening of funds: because only the individual states have economic resources, a financial stock that may be able to put things in order.
They have the means and the authority to use them: under the circumstances, they have two invaluable resources that probably no other market or any international organisation will ever have to this extent.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed by the crisis on the nation-state is fully in line with the fact that recent economic growth attaches increasing importance to a factor that is closely related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had already entered the abstract world of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, and were convinced that the global financial world was destined to rule the world, we had to realize that our future was increasingly dependent on things like water, crops and oil.
Things that can be transported from one side of the planet to another, yet are completely linked to a demarcated place, an area.
So whoever controls the area has much more cards than who, unfortunately, was born in a place where there is no crop, no oil, and no water.
This leads me to the second novelty, which suggests a kind of fault line.
Anyone who says territory, state, government must also say politics, in other words leadership.
From this point of view, the economic crisis seems to produce two congruent phenomena:
On the one hand, the objective recognition of the need for credible leadership, people who can take control of events.
On the other hand, the current leadership, especially economic leaders, who have proved completely incompetent and have proven that there are many areas of obscurity ahead of them.
Together, the two are even more important and, in a sense, more disturbing: a sense of loss of credit, impatience, inadequacy and separation that affects the entire leadership elite in an increasing number of Western countries.
Thus, it seems that a growing number of people are convinced that the time of the social elite at the top is over. It has expired before their actions, experiences, lifestyles, culture, in the complex sense of the word, have been embraced. With this, the social elite is increasingly alienated from the opinion of the majority.
In short, the need for leadership, in a veiled form, feeds a diverse but strong delegation movement against the ruling class and the traditional political system. This manifests itself in the unexpected "revolts" of voters, or in recent times in sudden changes in public sentiment. For example, the rise of conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, the collapse of Labour unity in Great Britain, or the victory of American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps the right side).
It seems that the traditional elite, along with its parties, programs, and even its customs, press, and renowned intellectuals, are less and less able to understand, and therefore less and less able to represent what has been going on in the deeper layers of Western society for some time.
Nevertheless, speaking of “the imminent revolt of the masses” would be frankly an exaggeration.
But it doesn't hurt to walk with your eyes open.
