Good-bye, old Cinema Paradiso, the time of old movie halls in the cities is over
Traditional cinemas are closing for the benefit of Multiplex.
"A city without cinemas, a blind city, is like a face without eyes."
The pictures taken by director Giuseppe Tornatore represent effectively everything that happens in Italian cities, but also in rural regions.
The displacement of cinemas - the appearance of large multi-room cinemas in the suburbs and, as a result, the atrophy of one-room cinemas in the city centres - seems to be an inevitable and irreversible process, but at the same time bears all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
When historical and reminiscence-filled places disappear, “it’s like a friend of ours, a friend with whom we shared our journey and many experiences,” says the director of Cinema Paradiso. The film, which was an Oscar twenty years ago and the grand prize of the Cannes Festival for Tornatore, tells the lyrical story of a small-town cinema, the yearning for a cinema experience that may have been lost forever.
The data provided by Anec, the largest association of operators, speaks clearly: 316 traditional cinemas have closed in the last five years. The biggest loss was recorded by cinemas in large cities: 10 cinemas have closed in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Emilia-Romagna is at the forefront of the most affected regions, which lost 82 one-room cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardia (41).
And the fact that multiplexes are responsible for their disappearance is no more evident than the highest number of newly opened multi-room cinemas in these three regions of Italy: in the last five years, the number of halls in Lombardy has increased by 195, 81 in Tuscany and the same in Emilia-Romagna.
"The number of units in Italy has increased irrationally," says Anec President Paolo Protti. "It's okay to build new facilities, but we should also ensure the survival of those already in existence, because when a city cinema closes, not all walkers are willing to go to the multiplexes.
Not to mention unfunded funds to support operators: the state’s overdue debt is estimated at around EUR 10 million.
From an ethical and moral point of view, it is shameful that the government does not comply with the laws in force.
To maintain the market, we would need EUR 16-18 million a year".
This is the first Italian city that, in its concern over the closures, decided to remedy the problem through an agreement between the municipality and Anec in order to protect and boost single-room cinemas in the city and downtown.
The provisions would include tax incentives for operators and benefits for the public to facilitate accessibility: viewers can drive into restricted areas and park at reduced rates in certain parking lots.
"I like this initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities, even with the introduction of other measures, will follow the example of Bologna.
However, it is also certain that traditional cinemas, in order to be able to fight the rule of multiplexes, need to improve sound and image quality, because today's audience is much more demanding.
The preservation of traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of Supercinema in Bagheria, where I spent my childhood and youth, gave me the spark that ultimately made me do Cinema Paradiso, although I had been thinking about it for 10 years.
