The energy comes from the waves, and now comes the big ones
It’s an inexhaustible source of energy that makes up 70 percent of the planet’s surface and is only now being discovered by major international energy companies.
Waves, sea currents, tidal tides, all renewable energy sources that have been eyed by giants like Chevron, who are now trying to get their hands on it.
For a hundred years, they've been researching how to get energy from sea movements. In the '70s, during the first oil crisis, research increased.
Around 1980, when oil prices fell, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but today the demands of environmental protection and the re-increase in oil prices give the sector a new impetus.
According to the 2007 World Energy Council (WEC) in London, 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be covered by marine wave facilities.
This is twice the amount that nuclear power plants currently produce.
In addition, there would be currents and tides.
The giants are on the move.
Enersis was the first company to commit to marine energy and signed an agreement in 2005 on a power plant in northern Portugal.
It seemed like a revolutionary step when the signature was announced.
Two years have passed since then, and more and more companies are opting for marine energy, including those who have been committed to traditional energy.
“Chevron is studying technologies that harness the energy of the oceans and is considering the possibility of working with us,” a spokesman for the US oil giant’s associate firm, the Wall Street Journal, said in a statement.
The cooperation in question concerns the acquisition of a permit for the launch of the Alaskan offshore energy project issued by the US Energy Commission.
This is of no small importance, especially considering that the US is in the process of extracting oil in Alaska, and President Bush has recently launched a plan for further drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. in New York and Ocean Power in New Jersey are also on the road to extract energy from the sea. The amounts invested so far, as far as the details are known, show increasing interest.
Technology is waiting to be developed.
Experts say it is still a rudimentary technology, especially because the energy that can be obtained from the sea does not dispel doubts about the environmental impact.
The existing facilities, such as those in Portugal or Scotland, are all small in size and therefore do not pose a major problem for the ecosystem.
However, in order to produce energy on a larger scale, installations need to have a more significant environmental impact.
There are several options: Ocean Power, for example, uses a connected buoy system.
The shocks generated by the waves and moving the buoys up and down are converted into hydraulic pressure by the pistons and cylinders placed in them.
The pressure rotates a turbine that feeds a generator.
Electricity goes to land on cables under the sea.
For the time being, there are four similar facilities in the planning phase, which are just waiting for federal permission to use part of the energy produced in a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started producing energy for a shopping mall and a parking lot with the help of six underwater turbines in the East River Strait of New York.
At a tide, the movement of water rotates the turbine blades, and this rotation feeds the generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of partners who are only waiting for permits to use energy.
Waves after tides.
At present, special attention should be paid to the opportunities that can be exploited through tidal tides.
Although it is a temporary phenomenon, tidal tides are more predictable than wind, sun or waves, so they can be considered a more reliable source of energy.
New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as the other coastal states, spent $7.5 million in 2008 to exploit the energy provided by the tides, which is expected to increase to 35 million in 2009.
